t=Saeed|date=2011-07-10|website=The News Tribe|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and Orangi Town was re-organized as part of [[Karachi West District]] in 2015.\n\n== Location ==\nOrangi Town was bordered by [[New Karachi Town]] to the north across the Shahrah-e-Zahid Hussain, [[Gulberg Town, Karachi|Gulberg Town]] to the east across the [[Gujjar Nala]] stream, [[Liaquatabad Town]] to the south, and [[SITE Town]] to the west. There were 13 official neighborhoods, called Union Councils  \n\n== History ==\nThe federal government under [[Pervez Musharraf]], who seized power in a [[1999 Pakistani coup d'\u00e9tat|1999 coup d'etat]], introduced local government reforms in the year 2000, which eliminated the previous \"third tier of government\" ([[Divisions of Pakistan|administrative divisions]]) and replaced it with the fourth tier ([[Districts of Pakistan|districts]]). The effect in Karachi was the dissolution of the former [[Karachi Division]] in 2001, and the merging of its five districts to form a new Karachi City-District with eighteen autonomous constituent towns including Keamari Town. In 2011, the system was disbanded but remained in place for bureaucratic administration until 2015, when the [[Karachi Metropolitan Corporation]] system was reintroduced. In 2015, Keamari Town was re-organized as part of [[District of West Karachi|Karachi West]] district\n\n== Localities within Orangi Town ==\n[[Baloch Goth]]<br />[[Bilal Colony]]<br />[[Chisti Nagar]]<br />[[Raees Amrohi Colony]]<br />[[Data Nagar]]<br />[[Ghabool Town]]<br />[[Ghaziabad (Karachi)|Ghaziabad]]<br />[[Hanifabad]]<br />[[Haryana Colony]]<br />[[Iqbal Baloch Colony]]<br />[[Madina Colony (Orangi Town)|Madina Colony]]<br />[[Mohammad Nagar]]<br />[[Mominabad]]<br />[[Mujahidabad]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Akhtar Hameed Khan]]\n* [[Al-Jabbar Welfare Association ]]\n* [[City District Government Karachi]]\n* [[Karachi Health and Social Development Association]]\n* [[Khasa Hills]]\n* [[Orangi Charitable Trust]]\n* [[Orangi Nala]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project Society]]\n* [[Orangi Pilot Project]]\n* [[Orangi Research and Training Institute]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.orangitown.com Orangi Website]\n\n{{Orangi Town}}\n{{Orangi topics}}\n\n{{coord|24|57|N|66|58|E|display=title|region:PK_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n[[Category:Orangi Town| ]]\n[[Category:Squats in Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Alishernavoi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orangi_Town"}
{"title_page": "June 6", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n* [[913]] &ndash; The 8-year-old illegitimate son of [[Leo VI the Wise]], [[Constantine VII]], becomes nominal ruler of the [[Byzantine Empire]], under the [[regency]] of a seven-man council headed by Patriarch [[Nicholas Mystikos]], appointed by Constantine's uncle [[Alexander (Byzantine emperor)|Alexander III]] on his deathbed.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Dumbarton Oaks|author2=Philip Grierson|title=Catalogue of the Byzantine Coins in the Dumbarton Oaks Collection and in the Whittemore Collection: Leo III to Nicephorus III, 717 - 1801|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dDH8GM4xrysC&pg=PA526|date=June 1973|publisher=Dumbarton Oaks|isbn=978-0-88402-045-5|pages=526}}</ref>\n*[[1513]] &ndash; [[Italian Wars]]: [[Battle of Novara (1513)|Battle of Novara]]. [[Switzerland|Swiss]] troops defeat the French under [[Louis II de la Tr\u00e9moille]], forcing the French to abandon [[Milan]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hans Delbr_ck|title=The Dawn of Modern Warfare|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MsBMpfMVp-AC&pg=PA78|year=1990|publisher=U of Nebraska Press|isbn=0-8032-6586-7|pages=78}}</ref> Duke [[Massimiliano Sforza]] is restored.\n*[[1523]] &ndash; [[Gustav Vasa]], the Swedish regent, is elected [[Monarchy of Sweden|King of Sweden]], marking a symbolic end to the [[Kalmar Union]]. This is the Swedish national day.<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Douglas Lockhart|title=Sweden in the Seventeenth Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nNYcBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA6|date=13 February 2004|publisher=Macmillan International Higher Education|isbn=978-0-230-80255-1|pages=6}}</ref>\n*[[1586]] &ndash; [[Francis Drake]]'s forces raid [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]] in [[Spanish Florida]].\n*[[1644]] &ndash; The [[Qing dynasty]] [[Manchu people|Manchu]] forces led by the [[Shunzhi Emperor]] capture Beijing during the collapse of the [[Ming dynasty]]. \n*[[1674]] &ndash; [[Shivaji]], founder of the [[Maratha Empire]], is crowned.<ref>{{cite book |first=Pradeep |last=Barua | title=The State at War in South Asia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FIIQhuAOGaIC&pg=PA42 | year= 2005 | publisher=University of Nebraska Press | isbn=978-0-8032-1344-9 | page=42 }}</ref>\n*[[1749]] &ndash; The [[Conspiracy of the Slaves]] in [[Malta]] is discovered.\n*[[1762]] &ndash; [[Seven Years' War]]: British forces begin a siege of [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], and temporarily capture the city in the [[Battle of Havana (1762)|Battle of Havana]]. \n*[[1808]] &ndash; [[Napoleon]]'s brother, [[Joseph Bonaparte]], is crowned [[Monarchy of Spain|King of Spain]].\n*[[1809]] &ndash; Sweden promulgates a new [[Instrument of Government (1809)|Constitution]], which restores political power to the [[Riksdag of the Estates]] after 20 years of [[enlightened absolutism]]. At the same time, [[Charles XIII of Sweden|Charles XIII]] is elected to succeed [[Gustav IV Adolf of Sweden|Gustav IV Adolf]] as [[Monarchy of Sweden|King of Sweden]].\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[War of 1812]]: [[Battle of Stoney Creek]]: A British force of 700 under [[John Vincent (general)|John Vincent]] defeats an American force twice its size under [[William H. Winder|William Winder]] and [[John Chandler]].\n*[[1822]] &ndash; [[Alexis St. Martin]] is accidentally shot in the stomach, leading to [[William Beaumont]]'s studies on digestion.\n*[[1832]] &ndash; The [[June Rebellion]] in Paris is put down by the National Guard.\n*[[1844]] &ndash; The [[YMCA|Young Men's Christian Association]] (YMCA) is founded in London.\n*  1844   &ndash; The [[Glaciarium]], the world's first mechanically frozen [[ice rink]], opens.\n*[[1857]] &ndash; [[Sophia of Nassau]] marries the future King [[Oscar II of Sweden|Oscar II]] of [[Sweden\u2013Norway]].\n*[[1859]] &ndash; Australia: Queensland is established as a separate [[crown colony|colony]] from [[New South Wales]] ([[Queensland Day]]).\n*[[1862]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Battle of Memphis]]: [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces capture [[Memphis, Tennessee]], from the [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]].\n*[[1882]] &ndash; More than 100,000 inhabitants of [[Bombay]] are supposedly killed in the so-called '[[Bombay Cyclone of 1882 (hoax)|Bombay Cyclone of 1882]]', but this has proved a [[hoax]] and did not happen.\n*  1882   &ndash; The [[Shewa]]n forces of [[Menelik II of Ethiopia]] defeat the [[Gojjam]]e army in the [[Battle of Embabo]]. The Shewans capture Negus Tekle Haymanot of Gojjam, and their victory leads to a Shewan hegemony over the territories south of the [[Abay River]].\n*[[1889]] &ndash; The [[Great Seattle Fire]] destroys all of downtown Seattle.\n*[[1892]] &ndash; The [[Chicago \"L\"#History|Chicago \"L\"]] elevated rail system begins operation.\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Governor of Colorado|Governor]] [[Davis H. Waite]] orders the [[Colorado]] [[U.S. National Guard|state militia]] to protect and support the miners engaged in the [[Cripple Creek miners' strike of 1894|Cripple Creek miners' strike]].\n*[[1909]] &ndash; French troops capture [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]] (in modern-day [[Chad]]) and install a puppet [[sultan]] in the [[Ouaddai Empire]].\n*[[1912]] &ndash; The eruption of [[Novarupta]] in Alaska begins. It is the largest [[volcanic]] eruption of the 20th century.\n*[[1916]] &ndash; With the death of Yuan Shikai, who has ruled much of China since 1912, the central government virtually collapses in the face of warlords who assert themselves, including Sun Yat-sen.\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[World War I]]: [[Battle of Belleau Wood]]: The [[U.S. Marine Corps]] suffers its worst single day's casualties while attempting to recapture the wood at [[Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry]].\n*[[1919]] &ndash; The [[Republic of Prekmurje]] ends.\n*[[1921]] &ndash; [[Southwark Bridge]] in London is opened to traffic by King [[George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]].\n*[[1932]] &ndash; The [[Revenue Act of 1932]] is enacted, creating the first [[gas tax]] in the United States, at a rate of 1 cent per [[US gallon]] ({{1/4}}\u00a2/L) sold.\n*[[1933]] &ndash; The first [[drive-in theater]] opens in [[Camden, New Jersey]], United States.\n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[New Deal]]: The U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] signs the [[Securities Exchange Act of 1934]] into law, establishing the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]].\n*[[1939]] &ndash; Judge [[Joseph Force Crater]], known as the \"Missingest Man in New York\", is [[Declared death in absentia|declared legally dead]].\n*[[1942]] &ndash; [[World War II]]: [[Battle of Midway]]. U.S. Navy dive bombers sink the [[Japanese cruiser Mikuma|Japanese cruiser ''Mikuma'']] and four Japanese carriers.\n*[[1944]] &ndash;  World War II: The [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] invasion of Normandy\u2014codenamed [[Operation Overlord]]\u2014begins with the execution of [[Normandy landings|Operation Neptune]] (commonly referred to as [[D-Day]]), the landing of 155,000 Allied troops on the beaches of [[Normandy]] in France. The Allied soldiers quickly break through the [[Atlantic Wall]] and push inland in the largest amphibious military operation in history.\n*[[1946]] &ndash; The [[Basketball Association of America]] is founded in [[New York City]]; the BAA was the precursor to the modern [[National Basketball Association]].\n*[[1954]] &ndash; The grand opening of the [[Statue of Yuriy Dolgorukiy, Moscow|sculpture of Yuriy Dolgorukiy]] took place in [[Moscow]]. This statue is one of the main monuments of Moscow.\n*[[1964]] &ndash; Under a temporary order, the [[Rocket experiments in the area of Cuxhaven|rocket launches at Cuxhaven]], Germany are terminated. They never resume.\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Soyuz program]]: ''[[Soyuz 11]]'' is launched.\n*  1971   &ndash; A [[Hughes Airwest Flight 706|midair collision]] between a [[Hughes Airwest]] [[Douglas DC-9]] [[Jet airliner|jetliner]] and a [[United States Marine Corps]] [[McDonnell Douglas]] [[F-4 Phantom II]] [[fighter aircraft|jet fighter]] near [[Duarte, California]], claims 50 lives.<!--Resulted in policy change; notable-->\n*  1971   &ndash; [[Vietnam War]]: The [[Battle of Long Khanh]] between [[Australian Army|Australian]] and [[People's Army of Vietnam|Vietnamese communist forces]] begins.\n*[[1974]] &ndash; A new [[Instrument of Government (1974)|Instrument of Government]] is promulgated making Sweden a [[Parliamentarism|parliamentary]] monarchy.\n*[[1981]] &ndash; [[Bihar train disaster]]: A passenger train travelling between Mansi and [[Saharsa]], India, jumps the tracks at a bridge crossing the [[Bagmati River]]. The government places the official death toll at 268 plus another 300 missing; however, it is generally believed that the death toll is closer to 1,000.\n*[[1982]] &ndash; The [[1982 Lebanon War|Lebanon War]] begins. Forces under [[Israel]]i [[Defense Minister]] [[Ariel Sharon]] invade [[southern Lebanon]] during [[Operation Peace for the Galilee]], eventually reaching as far north as the capital [[Beirut]].\n*[[1985]] &ndash; The grave of \"Wolfgang Gerhard\" is opened in [[Embu das Artes|Embu]], Brazil; the exhumed remains are later proven to be those of [[Josef Mengele]], [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]]'s \"Angel of Death\"; Mengele is thought to have drowned while swimming in February 1979.\n*[[1993]] &ndash; [[Mongolia]] holds its first direct presidential elections.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[China Northwest Airlines Flight 2303]] crashes near [[Xi'an]], China, killing all 160 people on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19940606-1|title=ASN Aircraft accident Tupolev Tu-154M B-2610 Xian-Xianyang International Airport (XIY)|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref>\n*[[2002]] &ndash; [[2002 Eastern Mediterranean event|Eastern Mediterranean event]]. A [[near-Earth asteroid]] estimated at ten meters in diameter explodes over the Mediterranean Sea between Greece and [[Libya]]. The explosion is estimated to have a force of 26 [[kiloton]]s, slightly more powerful than the [[Nagasaki atomic bomb]].\n*[[2004]] &ndash; [[Tamil language|Tamil]] is established as a \"[[Languages of India#Classical languages of India|classical language]]\" by the President of India, Dr [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]], in a joint sitting of the two houses of the Indian Parliament.\n*[[2005]] &ndash; In ''[[Gonzales v. Raich]]'', the [[United States Supreme Court]] upholds a federal law banning [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], including [[medical marijuana]].\n\n==Births==\n<!--Please do not add yourself, non-notable people, fictional characters, or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. \nDo not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence. If there are multiple people in the same birth year, put them in alphabetical order. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. -->\n*[[1236]] &ndash; [[Wen Tianxiang]], Chinese general and scholar (d. 1283)\n*[[1243]] &ndash; [[Alix of Brittany, Dame de Pontarcy]]; Breton noble (d. 1288)\n*[[1296]] &ndash; [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw of Legnica]] (d. 1352)\n*[[1436]] &ndash; [[Regiomontanus]], German mathematician, astronomer, and bishop (d. 1476)\n*[[1519]] &ndash; [[Andrea Cesalpino]], Italian philosopher, physician, and botanist (d. 1603)\n*[[1539]] &ndash; [[Catherine Vasa]], Regent of East Frisia (d. 1610)\n*[[1553]] &ndash; [[Bernardino Baldi]], Italian mathematician and author (d. 1617)\n*[[1556]] &ndash; [[Edward la Zouche, 11th Baron Zouche]], English politician and diplomat (d. 1625)\n*[[1576]] &ndash; [[Giovanni Diodati]], Swiss-Italian minister, theologian, and academic (d. 1649)\n*[[1580]] &ndash; [[Godefroy Wendelin]], Belgian astronomer and author (d. 1667)\n*[[1584]] &ndash; [[Yuan Chonghuan]], politician, military general and writer (d. 1630)\n*[[1599]] &ndash; [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]