]] &ndash; [[Jo\u00e3o de Castro]], Portuguese soldier and politician, [[List of governors of Portuguese India|Governor of Portuguese India]] (b. 1500)\n*[[1561]] &ndash; [[Ridolfo Ghirlandaio]], Italian painter (b. 1483)\n*[[1583]] &ndash; [[Nakagawa Kiyohide]], Japanese daimy\u014d (b. 1556)\n*[[1659]] &ndash; [[Nadira Banu Begum]], Mughal princess (b. 1618)\n*[[1661]] &ndash; [[Martino Martini]], Italian Jesuit missionary (b. 1614)\n*[[1730]] &ndash; [[Alain Emmanuel de Co\u00ebtlogon]], French general (b. 1646)\n*[[1740]] &ndash; [[Alexander Spotswood]], Moroccan-American colonial and politician, [[List of colonial governors of Virginia|Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]] (b. 1676)\n*[[1784]] &ndash; [[Joan van der Capellen tot den Pol]], Dutch politician (b. 1741)\n*[[1799]] &ndash; [[Patrick Henry]], American lawyer and politician, 1st [[Governor of Virginia]] (b. 1736)\n*[[1813]] &ndash; [[Alexandre-Th\u00e9odore Brongniart]], French architect, designed the [[H\u00f4tel de Mademoiselle de Cond\u00e9]] (b. 1739)\n*  1813   &ndash; [[Antonio Cachia]], Maltese architect, engineer and archaeologist (b. 1739)\n*[[1832]] &ndash; [[Jeremy Bentham]], English jurist and philosopher (b. 1748)\n*[[1840]] &ndash; [[Marcellin Champagnat]], French priest and saint, founded the [[Marist Brothers]] (b. 1789)\n*[[1843]] &ndash; [[Friedrich H\u00f6lderlin]], German poet and author (b. 1770)\n*[[1861]] &ndash; [[Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour]], Italian politician, 1st [[Prime Minister of Italy]] (b. 1810)\n*[[1862]] &ndash; [[Turner Ashby]], American colonel (b. 1828)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[William Quantrill]], American captain (b. 1837)\n*[[1878]] &ndash; [[Robert Stirling]], Scottish minister and engineer, invented the [[stirling engine]] (b. 1790)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Henri Vieuxtemps]], Belgian violinist and composer (b. 1820)\n*[[1883]] &ndash; [[Ciprian Porumbescu]], Romanian composer and poet (b. 1853)\n*[[1891]] &ndash; [[John A. Macdonald]], Scottish-Canadian lawyer and politician, 1st [[Prime Minister of Canada]] (b. 1815)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Yuan Shikai]], Chinese general and politician, 2nd [[President of the Republic of China]] (b. 1859)\n*[[1922]] &ndash; [[Lillian Russell]], American actress and singer (b. 1860)\n*[[1924]] &ndash; [[William Pirrie, 1st Viscount Pirrie]], Irish businessman and politician, [[Lord Mayor of Belfast]] (b. 1847) \n*[[1934]] &ndash; [[Julije Kempf]], Croatian historian and author (b. 1864)\n*[[1935]] &ndash; [[Julian Byng, 1st Viscount Byng of Vimy]], English field marshal and politician, 12th [[Governor-General of Canada]] (b. 1862)\n*[[1941]] &ndash; [[Louis Chevrolet]], Swiss-American race car driver and businessman, founded [[Chevrolet]] and [[Frontenac Motor Corporation]] (b. 1878)\n*[[1943]] &ndash; [[Pandelis Pouliopoulos]], Greek politician (b. 1900)\n*[[1946]] &ndash; [[Gerhart Hauptmann]], German novelist, poet, and playwright, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1862)\n*[[1947]] &ndash; [[James Agate]], English author and critic (b. 1877)\n*[[1948]] &ndash; [[Auguste and Louis Lumi\u00e8re|Louis Lumi\u00e8re]], French director, producer, and screenwriter (b. 1864)\n*[[1951]] &ndash; [[Olive Tell]], American actress (b. 1894)\n*[[1954]] &ndash; [[Fritz Kasparek]], Austrian mountaineer and author (b. 1910)\n*[[1955]] &ndash; [[Max Meldrum]], Scottish-Australian painter and educator (b. 1875)\n*[[1961]] &ndash; [[Carl Jung]], Swiss psychiatrist and psychotherapist (b. 1875)\n*[[1962]] &ndash; [[Yves Klein]], French painter (b. 1928)\n*  1962   &ndash; [[Tom Phillis]], Australian motorcycle racer (b. 1934)\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[William Baziotes]], American painter and academic (b. 1912)\n*[[1968]] &ndash; [[Randolph Churchill]], English journalist and politician (b. 1911)\n*  1968   &ndash; [[Robert F. Kennedy]], American soldier, lawyer, and politician, 64th [[United States Attorney General]] (b. 1925)\n*  1968   &ndash; [[K\u00e2z\u0131m \u00d6zalp]], Turkish general and politician, 3rd [[List of Ministers of National Defence of Turkey|Turkish Minister of National Defence]] (b. 1880)\n*[[1975]] &ndash; [[Larry Blyden]], American actor (b. 1925)\n*[[1976]] &ndash; [[J. Paul Getty]], American businessman, founded the [[Getty Oil|Getty Oil Company]] (b. 1892)\n*[[1979]] &ndash; [[Jack Haley]], American actor (b. 1897)\n*[[1980]] &ndash; [[Ruth Aarons]], American table tennis player and manager (b. 1918)\n*[[1982]] &ndash; [[Kenneth Rexroth]], American poet and academic (b. 1905)\n*[[1983]] &ndash; [[Hans Leip]], German author, poet, and playwright (b. 1893)\n*[[1984]] &ndash; [[A. Bertram Chandler]], English-Australian soldier and author (b. 1912)\n*[[1991]] &ndash; [[Stan Getz]], American saxophonist (b. 1927)\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Barry Sullivan (actor)|Barry Sullivan]], American actor (b. 1912)\n*[[1996]] &ndash; [[George Davis Snell]], American geneticist and immunologist, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1903)\n*[[1997]] &ndash; [[Magda Gabor]], Hungarian-American actress and socialite (b. 1915)\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Dard]], French author and screenwriter (b. 1921)\n*[[2001]] &ndash; [[Suzanne Schiffman]], French screenwriter and director (b. 1939)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Ken Grimwood]], American author (b. 1944)\n*  2003   &ndash; [[Dave Rowberry]], English singer-songwriter and pianist  (b. 1940)\n*[[2005]] &ndash; [[Anne Bancroft]], American actress (b. 1931)\n*  2005   &ndash; [[Dana Elcar]], American actor (b. 1927)\n*[[2006]] &ndash; [[Arnold Newman]], American photographer and educator (b. 1918)\n*  2006   &ndash; [[Billy Preston]], American singer-songwriter, pianist, and actor (b. 1946)\n*  2006   &ndash; [[Camille Sandorfy]], Hungarian-Canadian chemist and academic (b. 1920)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Jean Dausset]], French-Spanish immunologist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1916)\n*  2009   &ndash; [[Jim Owens]], American football player and coach (b. 1927)\n*[[2010]] &ndash; [[Marvin Isley]], American singer-songwriter and bass player (b. 1953)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Vladimir Krutov]], Russian ice hockey player (b. 1960)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Manuel Preciado Rebolledo]], Spanish footballer and coach (b. 1957)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Mykola Volosyanko]], Ukrainian footballer and manager (b. 1972)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Jerome Karle]], American chemist and academic, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1918)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Eugen Merzbacher]], German-American physicist and academic (b. 1921)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Tom Sharpe]], English-Spanish author and academic (b. 1928)\n*  2013   &ndash; [[Esther Williams]], American swimmer and actress (b. 1921)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Ado Bayero]], Nigerian politician and diplomat (b. 1930)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Eric Hill]], English-American author and illustrator (b. 1927)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Lorna Wing]], English psychiatrist and physician (b. 1928)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Pierre Brice]], French actor (b. 1929)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Vincent Bugliosi]], American lawyer and author (b. 1934)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Ronnie Gilbert]], American singer-songwriter (b. 1926)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Ludv\u00edk Vacul\u00edk]], Czech journalist and author (b. 1926)\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Viktor Korchnoi]], Russian chess player (b. 1931)\n*  2016   &ndash; [[Peter Shaffer]], English playwright and screenwriter (b. 1926)\n* [[2018]] &ndash; [[Ralph Santolla]], American guitarist, [[Deicide (band)|Deicide]], [[Iced Earth]] (b. 1969)\n<!--Do not add yourself or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. No red links, please. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*Christian [[feast day]]:\n**[[Claudius of Besan\u00e7on|Claude the Thaumaturge]]\n**[[Gottschalk (Obotrite prince)|Gottschalk]]\n**[[Ini Kopuria]] ([[Church of England]], [[Episcopal Church (USA)|Episcopal Church]], [[Anglican Church of Melanesia]])\n**[[Marcellin Champagnat]]\n**[[Norbert of Xanten]]\n**[[June 6 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Engineer's Day]] ([[Taiwan]])\n*[[Public holidays in North Korea|Korean Children's Union Foundation Day]] ([[North Korea]])\n*[[Memorial Day (South Korea)]]\n*[[National Day of Sweden|National Day]], marks the end of the Danish-ruled [[Kalmar Union]]. ([[Sweden]])\n*[[Huntington's disease|National Huntington's Disease Awareness Day]] ([[United States]])\n*[[Normandy landings]] of the Allied Expeditionary Forces (D-Day), a.k.a. Operation Neptune, part of [[Operation Overlord]] (1944)\n*[[Queensland Day]] (Queensland)\n*[[Teachers' Day]] ([[Bolivia]])\n*[[UN Russian Language Day]] ([[United Nations]])\n\n==Christian eschatology==\n\nThe date of June 6, 2006 was significant for followers of [[Christian eschatology]], 6/6/6 being the \"[[Number of the Beast]]\".  [[Tim LaHaye]] and [[Jerry B. Jenkins]] chose this date to publish their novel ''[[The Rapture (novel)|The Rapture]]'', a [[Christian science fiction]] book with eschatological themes.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/june/6 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=06|day=06}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/June_6 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:June 06}}\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:June]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvents:Removed unnecessary link.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_6"}
{"title_page": "2003\u201304 FA Premier League", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{lead too long|date=May 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2009}}\n}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[Premier League|FA Premier League]]\n| season             = 2003\u201304\n| dates              = 16 August 2003\u201315 May 2004\n| winners            = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]<br>3rd Premier League title<br>13th [[List of English football champions|English title]]\n| relegated          = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]<br>[[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]<br>[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| continentalcup1    = [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]<br>[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]<br />[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] <br>[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]\n| continentalcup2    = [[2004\u201305 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]<br>[[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Thierry Henry]] (30 goals)\n| biggest home win   = [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] 6\u20131 [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]<br>{{small|(8 November 2003)}}<br>[[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 5\u20130 [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]<br>{{small|(9 November 2003)}}<br>[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 5\u20130 [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]<br>{{small|(16 April 2004)}}\n| biggest away win   = [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] 0\u20135 [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]<br>{{small|(20 September 2003)}}<br>[[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] 0\u20135 [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]<br>{{small|(31 January 2004)}}\n| highest scoring    = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 6\u20132 [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]<br>{{small|(18 October 2003)}}<br>[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] 4\u20134 [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]<br>{{small|(22 February 2004)}}<br>[[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] 5\u20133 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]<br>{{small|(20 March 2004)}}\n| matches            = 380\n| total goals        = 1012\n| longest wins       = 9 games<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/stats/england/premier-league/2003-2004/longest-sequences/full |title=English Premier League 2003\u201304 |publisher=statto.com |accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref><br />[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| longest unbeaten   = 38 games<ref name=\"stats\"/><br />[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| longest losses     = 6 games<ref name=\"stats\"/><br />[[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]\n| longest winless    = 14 games<ref name=\"stats\"/><br />[[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n| highest attendance = 67,758 <br />[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] v [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]<br>{{small|(31 January 2004)}}\n| lowest attendance  = 13,981<br />[[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] v [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]<br>{{small|(12 April 2004)}}\n| average attendance = \n| prevseason         = [[2002\u201303 FA Premier League|2002\u201303]]\n| nextseason         = [[2004\u201305 FA Premier League|2004\u201305]]\n}}\n[[Image:Trophy presentation Highbury 2004.JPG|thumb|Arsenal captain [[Patrick Vieira]] lifting the trophy at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] ]]\nThe '''2003\u201304 FA Premier League''' (known as the '''FA [[Barclaycard]] Premiership''' for sponsorship reasons) was the 12th season of the [[Premier League]]. Arsenal were the champions and Chelsea, who had spent heavily throughout the season, were the runners up. Arsenal ended the season [[The Invincibles (football)|without a single defeat]] \u2013 the first team ever to do so in a 38-game league season and the second team overall (the first was [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] in 1889, 115 years earlier, during a 22-game league season).\n\n==Season summary==\n\nHaving qualified for the Champions' League the previous season, Chelsea were bolstered by a \u00a3100&nbsp;million outlay on world-class players, a spree funded by the extensive financial resources of their new owner [[Roman Abramovich]]. Manchester United's attack was as strong as ever thanks to free-scoring [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]], but the midfield was weakened following the \u00a325&nbsp;million pre-season sale of [[David Beckham]] to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], and the centre of defence suffered a more severe setback after [[Rio Ferdinand]] was ruled out for the final four months of the season after being found guilty of the \"failure or refusal to take a drugs test\". The case of Rio Ferdinand started a debate about punishments relating to drug testing in football, with there being differing views on whether the punishment was too harsh or too lenient. Ferdinand's club sought to make direct comparisons with an earlier case of Manchester City reserve player who had in fact committed a lesser drug testing offence and as a result escaped with only a fine.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/motive-is-always-considered-in-deciding-guilt-576995.html | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Motive is always considered in deciding guilt | first=Nick | last=Harris | date=18 December 2003 | accessdate=21 April 2010}}</ref> [[Manchester City F.C.|City]] themselves had just moved from [[Maine Road]] to the [[City of Manchester Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/the-club/club-history|title=Club History|publisher=Manchester City Football Club }}</ref>\n\nArsenal, meanwhile, had only signed German goalkeeper [[Jens Lehmann]] in the 2003 close season, but French striker [[Thierry Henry]] was instrumental in Arsenal's success. Away from the Premier League, [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]]'s team suffered disappointment in the cup competitions. They were knocked-out by [[2003\u201304 Football League Cup|League Cup]] eventual winners Middlesbrough in the semi-finals. They lost their defence of the [[2003\u201304 FA Cup|FA Cup]] (which they held for two seasons in a row) after losing to eventual winners Manchester United in the semi-final. Arsenal were knocked out of the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] quarter-finals by Chelsea (3\u20132 on aggregate). These blows in the FA Cup and Champions League came within a few days of each other, and it was feared that Arsenal might squander their lead of the Premier League for the second successive season, but Arsenal thumped [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] only days later. Arsenal's [[The Invincibles (football)|Invincibles]] finished the season with 26 wins, 12 draws, 0 defeats and 90 points.\n\nThe three relegation spots were occupied by three teams bracketed together on 33 points. [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]] and [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] followed the trend of many other newly promoted Premier League clubs and were relegated just one season after reaching the top division. The other relegation place went to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], whose playing fortunes had dipped in the past two seasons after [[David O'Leary]] was sacked as manager and club debts had risen so high that many star players had to be sold. As a result, Leeds were finally relegated from the Premier League after 14 years of top division football \u2013 just three seasons after they had reached the Champions League semifinals.\n\nIn his third season as Middlesbrough manager, [[Steve McClaren]] had guided the Teessiders to their first ever major trophy \u2013 sealed with a 2\u20131 win over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] final. McClaren was also the first English manager to win a major trophy since Brian Little guided [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] to League Cup success in 1996. He was also the first manager to take Middlesbrough into European competition \u2013 they would be competing in the 2004\u201305 [[UEFA Cup]].\n\n==Teams==\nTwenty teams competed in the league&nbsp;\u2013 the top seventeen teams from the previous season and the three teams promoted from the [[2002\u201303 Football League First Division|First Division]]. The promoted teams were [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], returning to the top flight after an absence of fifteen, one and nineteen years respectively. This was also both Portsmouth and Wolverhampton Wanderers' first season in the Premier League. They replaced [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] after spending time in the top flight for ten, one and four years respectively.\n\n===Stadiums and Locations===\n{{location map+ |England |width=440 |float=right |caption=Locations of the 2003\u201304 Premier League teams |places=\n{{location map~ |England |lat=51.5155|long=-0.0922|label_size=80|label=London|mark=Blue pog.svg|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=52.4977|long=-1.9057|label_size=80|label=West Midlands|mark=Yellow pog.svg|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=53.728569 |long=-2.489206 |label_size=80|label=[[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|{{nowrap|Blackburn Rovers}}]]|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=53.580578 |long=-2.535644 |label_size=80|label=[[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|{{nowrap|Bolton Wanderers}}]]|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=53.438846 |long=-2.966285 |label_size=80|label=[[Everton F.C.|Everton]]|position=left}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=53.704069 |long=-1.341731 |label_size=80|label=[[Leeds United F.C.|{{nowrap|Leeds United}}]]|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=52.620392 |long=-1.142267 |label_size=80|label=[[Leicester City F.C.|{{nowrap|Leicester City}}]]|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |England |lat=53.430845 |long=-2.960823 |label_size=80|label=[[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpo