9    = {{PH wikidata|expenditure}} {{PH wikidata|expenditure_point_in_time}} \n| demographics1_title10  = Expenditure Rank\n| demographics1_info10   = \n| demographics_type2     = \n| demographics2_title1   = Electricity\n| demographics2_info1    =  \n| demographics2_title2   = Water\n| demographics2_info2    =  \n| demographics2_title3   = Telecommunications\n| demographics2_info3    = \n| demographics2_title4   = Cable TV\n| demographics2_info4    =\n| demographics2_title5   = \n| demographics2_info5    =\n| demographics2_title6   = \n| demographics2_info6    =\n| demographics2_title7   = \n| demographics2_info7    =\n| demographics2_title8   = \n| demographics2_info8    =\n| demographics2_title9   = \n| demographics2_info9    =\n| demographics2_title10  = \n| demographics2_info10   =\n| blank_name_sec1        = {{PH wikidata|climate_title}}\n| blank_info_sec1        = {{PH wikidata|climate_type}}\n| blank1_name_sec1       = Spoken languages\n| blank1_info_sec1       = [[Cebuano language#Davaoe\u00f1o Cebuano|Cebuano]], [[Kalagan language|Kalagan]], [[English language|English]], [[Chavacano language|Chavacano]], [[Davaoe\u00f1o language|Native Davaoe\u00f1o]] and other minority languages <small>([[Manobo languages]], [[Tausug language|Tausug]], [[Sama language|Sama]], [[Iranun language|Iranun]], [[Tagabawa language|Tagabawa]], [[Giangan language|Giangan]], [[Maguindanao language|Maguindanao]], [[Maranao language|Maranao]], [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]], [[Philippine Hokkien|Hokkien]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Korean language|Korean]])</small>\n| blank2_name_sec1       = Sister localities\n| blank2_info_sec1       = \n| blank3_name_sec1       = \n| blank3_info_sec1       = \n| blank4_name_sec1       = \n| blank4_info_sec1       = \n| blank5_name_sec1       = \n| blank5_info_sec1       = \n| blank6_name_sec1       = \n| blank6_info_sec1       = \n| blank7_name_sec1       = \n| blank7_info_sec1       = \n| blank1_name_sec2       = Major religions\n| blank1_info_sec2       = \n| blank2_name_sec2       = Feast date\n| blank2_info_sec2       = \n| blank3_name_sec2       = Catholic diocese\n| blank3_info_sec2       =\n| blank4_name_sec2       = Patron saint \n| blank4_info_sec2       = \n| blank5_name_sec2       = \n| blank5_info_sec2       = \n| blank6_name_sec2       = \n| blank6_info_sec2       = \n| blank7_name_sec2       = \n| blank7_info_sec2       =\n| short_description      =\n| footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Davao City''', officially the '''City of Davao''' ({{lang-ceb|Dakbayan sa Dabaw}}), is a [[Cities of the Philippines#Classification|1st class highly urbanized city]] in the island of [[Mindanao]], [[Philippines]]. The city has a total land area of {{convert|2,443.61|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, making it the [[List of Philippine cities and municipalities by area|largest city in the Philippines in terms of land area]]. It is the [[List of Philippine cities and municipalities by population|third-most populous city in the Philippines]] after [[Quezon City]] and [[Manila]], the most populous city in the country outside [[Metro Manila]], and the most populous in Mindanao.{{PH census|2015}} As of the 2015 census the city had a population of 1,632,991.\n\nIt is geographically situated in the province of [[Davao del Sur]] and grouped under the province by the [[Philippine Statistics Authority]], but the city is governed and administered independently from it. The city is divided into three congressional districts, which are subdivided into 11 administrative districts with a total of 182 [[barangay]]s.\n\nDavao City is the center of [[Metro Davao]], the [[List of metropolitan areas in the Philippines|third-most populous metropolitan area in the Philippines]]. (As of the 2015 census this had a population of 2.5 million, compared with Metro Manila's 12.8 million and [[Metro Cebu]]'s 2.8 million.) The city serves as the main trade, commerce, and industry hub of Mindanao, and the regional center of [[Davao Region]]. Davao is home to [[Mount Apo]], the highest mountain in the Philippines. The city is also nicknamed the \"[[Durian]] Capital of the Philippines\".\n\n==Etymology==\nThe region's name is derived from its [[Bagobo]] origins. The Bagobos were indigenous to the Philippines. The word ''davao'' came from the phonetic blending of three [[Lumad peoples|Bagobo]] subgroups' names for the [[Davao River]], a major waterway emptying into the [[Davao Gulf]] near the city. The aboriginal Obos, who inhabit the hinterlands of the region, called the river ''Davah'' (with a gentle vowel ending, although later pronunciation is with a hard ''v'' or ''b''); the Clatta (or Giangan/Diangan) called it ''Dawaw'', and the Tagabawas called it ''Dabo''. To the Obos, ''davah'' also means \"a place beyond the high grounds\" (alluding to settlements at the mouth of the river surrounded by high, rolling hills).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ncca.gov.ph/subcommissions/subcommission-on-cultural-communities-and-traditional-arts-sccta/central-cultural-communities/bagobo/ |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=25 May 2018 |first1=Sonia D. |last1=Mangune |title=Bagobo |website=ncca.gov.ph |publisher=[[National Commission for Culture and the Arts]]}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Spanish era===\nAlthough the Spaniards began to explore the Davao Gulf area as early as the 16th century, Spanish influence was negligible in the Davao region until 1844, when the Spanish Governor General of the Philippines [[Narciso Claver\u00eda y Zald\u00faa, 1st Count of Manila|Narciso Claver\u00eda]] ordered the [[Davao Gulf]] region, including what is now Davao City, to be claimed Davao City for the Spanish Crown, despite protests by the [[Maguindanao Sultanate|Sultan of Maguindanao]]. Official colonization of the area, however, began in 1848 when an expedition of 70 men and women led by Jos\u00e9 Cruz de Uyanguren of [[Bergara|Vergara]], Spain, made a landing on the estuary of the [[Davao River]] the same year, intent on colonizing the vicinity. Nearby, a settlement was situated on the banks of the river, ruled by a Muslim Bagobo chieftain named Datu Bago.\n\nBeing the strongest chieftain in the region, Datu Bago imposed heavy tribute on the [[Mandaya]] tribes nearby, therefore also making him the most loathed chieftain in the region. Cruz de Uyanguren has orders from the higher authorities in [[Manila]] to colonize the Davao Gulf region, which included the Bagobo settlement on the northern riverbank. At this juncture, a Mandaya chieftain named Datu Daupan, who then ruled [[Samal Island]], came to him, seeking for an alliance against Datu Bago.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/philippines/sunstar-davao/20140706/281612418502280|title=PressReader.com - Your favorite newspapers and magazines.|website=www.pressreader.com}}</ref> The two chieftains were archrivals, and Cruz de Uyanguren took advantage of it, initiating an alliance between Spain and the Mandayas of Samal Island. Intent on taking the settlement for Spain, he and his men accordingly assaulted it, but the Bagobo natives fiercely resisted the attacks, which resulted in his Samal Mandaya allies to retreat and not fight again. Thus, a three-month long inconclusive battle for the possession of the settlement ensued which was only decided when an infantry company which sailed its way via warships from [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]] came in as reinforcements, thus ensuring the takeover of the settlement and its surroundings by the Spaniards while the defeated Bagobos fled further inland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philippinescities.com/davao-city-davao-del-sur/|title=Davao City History &#124; Tourist Spots and Festivals &#124; Philippines Cities}}</ref>\n\nAfter Cruz de Oyanguren defeated Bago, he founded the town of ''Nueva Vergara'', the future Davao, on 29 June 1848<ref>{{cite book |first1=Camilo T. |last1=Nunez |first2=Dante P. |last2=Diansay |year=2003 |title=Cateel Centennial Book |publisher=Local Government Unit of Cateel |pages=550}}</ref> in an area of mangrove swamps which is now Bolton Riverside, in honor of his home in Spain and becoming its first [[governor]]. Almost two years later in 29 February 1850, the province of ''[[:es:Nueva Guip\u00fazcoa|Nueva Guip\u00fazcoa]]'' was established via a royal decree,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalogo.bne.es/uhtbin/cgisirsi/0/x/0/05?searchdata1=bimo0001651973|title=Diccionario geogr\u00e1fico, estad\u00edstico, hist\u00f3rico de las islas Filipinas ... [Texto impreso]|first=Manuel|last=Buzeta|date=September 24, 1850|publisher=[s.n.]|via=catalogo.bne.es Library Catalog}}</ref> with the newly founded town as the capital, once again to honor his homeland in Spain. When he was the governor of the province, however, his plans of fostering a positive economic sway on the region backfired, which resulted in his eventual replacement under orders of the colonial government.\n\nThe province of Nueva Guipuzcoa was dissolved in 30 July 1860, as it became the Politico-Military Commandery of Davao.<ref>{{Cite book|title=El archipi\u00e9lago filipino. Colecci\u00f3n de datos geogr\u00e1ficos, estad\u00edsticos, cronol\u00f3gicos y cient\u00edficos, relativos al mismo, entrescados de anteriores obras \u00fa obtenidos con la propia observaci\u00f3n y estudio;|first=Jos\u00e9|last=Algu\u00e9|date=September 24, 1900|publisher=Impr. del gobierno|oclc = 351208}}</ref> By the clamor of its natives, a petition was given to the Spanish government to eventually rename Nueva Vergara into Davao, since they have called the town as the latter long from the time of its founding. It was eventually done in year 1867, and the town Nueva Vergara was officially given its present name Davao.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgedavao.net/special-feature/2016/03/18/the-governors-who-ruled-undivided-davao-191567/|title=The governors who ruled undivided Davao (1915\u201367)|first=Edge|last=Davao}}</ref>\n\nThe Spanish control of the town was unstable at best, as its [[Lumad]] and [[Moro people|Moro]] natives routinely resisted the attempts of the Spanish authorities to forcibly resettle them and convert them into Christians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/423712|title=Davao City's history: Vibrant and exciting|first=Cristina E.|last=Alivio|date=March 16, 2018|website=Sunstar}}</ref> Despite all these, however, such were all done in the goal of making the governance of the area easier, dividing the Christians both settlers and native converts and the Muslim Moros into several religion-based communities within the town.\n\n=== During the Philippine Revolution ===\nAs the [[Philippine Revolution]], having been fought for two years, neared its end in 1898, the expected departure of the Spanish authorities in Davao became apparent\u2014although they took no part in the war at all, for there were no revolutionary figures in the vicinity save a negligible pro-Filipino separatist rebel movement in the town of [[Santa Cruz, Davao del Sur|Santa Cruz]] in the south.<ref>{{cite web |author=Santa Cruz, Davao del Sur Government |title=History |url=http://www.stacruz.gov.ph/history.php |accessdate=21 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921053810/http://www.stacruz.gov.ph/history.php |archive-date=21 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When the war finally ended, as the Spanish authorities finally left the town, two Davaoe\u00f1o locals by the names of Pedro Layog and Jose M. Lerma represented the town and the region at the [[Revolutionary Government of the Philippines (1898\u20131899)|Malolos Congress of 1898]], therefore indicating Davao as a part of the nascent [[First Philippine Republic]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Ma. Christine Halili |title=Philippine History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gUt5v8ET4QYC&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=20 November 2018|isbn=9789712339349 |year=2004 }}</ref>\n\nThe period of Filipino revolutionary control of Davao did not last long, however, as the Americans landed at the town later the same year. There was no record of locals offering any sort of resistance to the Americans.\n\n===American period===\nAt the very instant the Americans began their administration of the town in 1900, economic opportunities quickly arose as huge swathes of its areas, mainly lush forests and fertile grasslands, were declared open for agricultural investment. A result of this, foreign businessmen especially Japanese entrepreneurs started settling the region, staking their claims on the vast lands of Davao and turned them into huge plantations of coconut and banana products.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgedavao.net/araw-ng-dabaw/2017/03/16/davao-city-80-years-making/|title=Davao City: 80 years in the making|first=Antonio|last=Figueroa}}</ref> In just a short period, Davao changed from a small and sparsely-inhabited town into a bustling economic center serving mainly the [[Davao Gulf]] region, heavily populated alongside natives by tens of thousands of settlers and economic migrants from [[Luzon]], [[Visayas]] and [[Japan]]. All of this led the [[Port of Davao]] to be established and opened the same year, in order to facilitate the international export of agricultural products from Davao.\n\n[[File:Davao City Hall.jpg|thumb|Davao City Hall was established in 1926 as the Municipal Hall when it was still a town.]]\nDavao was incorporated as a part of [[Moro Province]] from 1903 to 1914.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lawyerly.ph/laws/view/l9191|title=Act No. 787, (1903-06-01)|website=lawyerly.ph}}</ref> When the province was dissolved in 1914, it led to the establishment of [[Davao (province)|Davao Province]], with Davao town as its provincial capital. What is now the city's Legislative Council Building served as the provincial capitol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spdavao.wordpress.com/about/|title=Council at a Glance|date=April 24, 2007}}</ref> It was built in 1926, the same year the Davao Municipal Hall, now the City Hall, was constructed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://davaocitybybattad.blogspot.com/2011/04/city-hall-of-davao-city.html|title=Make It Davao: City Hall of Davao City|first=Do|last=Battad|date=April 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Davao Japantown in 1930s.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Man bicycling down street in old photo, with cars in background|Japan-town, Davao City (circa 1930s)]]\n\nBecause of the rapidly increasing progress of the town, on March 16, 1936, congressman Romualdo Quimpo from Davao filed ''Bill 609'' (passed as ''Commonwealth Act 51''), creating the City of Davao from the town of Davao and the municipal district of [[Districts of Davao City|Guianga]]. The bill called for the appointment of local officials by the president. By that time, the new city was already mostly populated with Japanese businessmen and settlers who then became its locals.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Macario |last1=Tiu |year=2005 |title=Davao, Reconstructing History from Text to Memory |publisher=Ateneo de Davao |isbn=9710392050}}</ref> Davao was inaugurated as a [[charter city]] on 16 October 1936 by President [[Manuel L. Quezon]];<ref name=\"TheCorpusJuris-CA51\">{{cite web |title=C.A. No. 51: An Act Creating the City of Davao |url=https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/commonwealth-acts/ca-no-51.php |website=The Corpus Juris |accessdate=21 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421143049/https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/commonwealth-acts/ca-no-51.php |archivedate=21 April 2019 |language=en |date=16 October 1936}}</ref> the charter came into effect in 1 March 1937. It was one of the first two towns in [[Mindanao]] to be converted into a city, the other being [[Zamboanga City|Zamboanga]].\n\n====Second World War====\n{{Main|Battle of Mindanao|Battle of Davao}}\nOn December 8, 1941, Japanese planes bombed the harbor, and from December 20 they [[Japanese invasion of Davao|landed forces]] and began an occupation of the city which lasted to 1945. Davao was among the earliest to be occupied by Japanese forces, and the city was immediately fortified as a bastion of Japanese defense.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\nThe city was subjected to extensive bombing by forces led by [[Douglas MacArthur]] before American forces landed in [[Leyte]] in October 1944. The [[Battle of Mindanao|Battle of Davao]] towards the end of [[World War II]] was one of the longest and bloodiest battles during the Philippine Liberation, and brought tremendous destruction to the city, setting back the economic and physical strides made before the Japanese occupation.\n\n===Philippine administration===\n[[File:Davao City Seal 1950.svg|thumb|right|Old seal of the city, [[National Historical Commission of the Philippines|NHCP]] version.]]\nDavao regained its status as the agricultural and economic hub of Mindanao after the war ended in 1945. Wood products such as plywood and timber, and More agricultural products being produced within the city, such as copra and other varieties of banana, became available for export. Some Japanese locals \u2014 80% percent of the city's population prior to the war's end \u2014 assimilated with the Filipino population, while others were expelled from the country by the Filipino locals, due to recent enmity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://davaoofthepast.com/2016/05/20/blog-post-title-3/|title=Davao history timeline|date=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, the [[Davao (province)|Province of Davao]] was divided into three provinces: [[Davao del Norte]], [[Davao Oriental]] and [[Davao del Sur]]. The city of Davao became part of Davao del Sur;<ref name=\"TheCorpusJuris-RA4867\">{{cite web |title=R.A. No. 4867: An Act Creating the Provinces of Davao del Norte, Davao del Sur and Davao Oriental |url=https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/republic-acts/ra-no-4867.php |website=The Corpus Juris |accessdate=21 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421143516/https://thecorpusjuris.com/legislative/republic-acts/ra-no-4867.php |archivedate=21 April 2019 |language=en |date=8 May 1967}}</ref> no longer the provincial capital, it became a commercial center of southern Mindanao. During the 1970s, Davao became the regional capital of southern Mindanao; with the reorganization, it became the regional capital of the [[Davao Region]] (Region XI) and highly urbanized city in the province of Davao del Sur.\n\nConflict inside the city became severe, murders in the streets occurring very frequently. This situation lasted until 1985, when locals formed the vigilante group \"Alsa Masa\" (People's Rise) to drive the causative elements from the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://census.gov.ph/content/davao-city-population-expected-double-24-years-results-2000-census-population-and-housing |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213015645/http://census.gov.ph/content/davao-city-population-expected-double-24-years-results-2000-census-population-and-housing |url-status=dead |archive-date=13 December 2014 |title=Davao City: Population Expected to Double in 24 Years (Results from the 2000 Census of Population and Housing, NSO) |accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nDavao City is approximately {{convert|588|mi|km}} southeast of Manila over land, and {{convert|971|km|nmi}} by sea. The city is located in southeastern Mindanao, on the northwestern shore of [[Davao Gulf]], opposite [[Samal, Davao del Norte|Samal Island]].\n\n===Topography===\n[[File:Davao river mouth.JPG|thumb|upright|200px|Mouth of the [[Davao River]] in Talomo District]]\n[[File:MountApo1.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|[[Mount Apo]] is the tallest mountain in the Philippines.]]\n\nDavao City's land, totaling about {{Convert|2,443.61|km2}}, is hilly in the west (the Marilog district) and slopes down to the southeastern shore. [[Mount Apo]], the highest peak in the Philippines, is located at the city's southwestern tip. Mount Apo National Park (the mountain and its surrounding vicinity), was inaugurated by [[President of the Philippines|President]] [[Manuel L. Quezon]] (in ''Proclamation 59'' of May 8, 1936) to protect the flora and fauna of the surrounding mountain range.<ref name=\"GovPH-Proc59\">{{cite web |title=Proclamation No. 59, s. 1936 |url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1936/05/09/proclamation-no-59-s-1936/ |website=Official Gazette of the Republic of the Philippines |accessdate=21 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421141347/https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1936/05/09/proclamation-no-59-s-1936/ |archivedate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Davao River]] is the city's primary drainage channel. Draining an area of over {{convert|1700|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}, the {{convert|160|km|mi|adj=on}} river begins in the town of [[San Fernando, Bukidnon]]. The mouth of the river is located at Barangay Bucana at Talomo District.\n\n===Climate===\nDavao has a [[tropical rainforest climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Af''), with little seasonal variation in temperature. The areological mechanism of the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] occurs more often than that of the [[trade wind]]s and because it experiences rare cyclones the climate is not purely equatorial but subequatorial. Average monthly temperatures are always above {{convert|26|C|1}}, and average monthly rainfall is above {{convert|77|mm|in|2}}. This gives the city a tropical climate, without a true [[dry season]]; while there is significant rainfall in winter, the largest rainfall occurs during the summer months (see climate chart, below).\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Davao City (1981\u20132010, extremes 1903\u20132012)\n| metric first = yes\n| single line  = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 35.0\n| Feb record high C = 36.7\n| Mar record high C = 36.7\n| Apr record high C = 37.0\n| May record high C = 37.3\n| Jun record high C = 35.2\n| Jul record high C = 35.6\n| Aug record high C = 36.0\n| Sep record high C = 35.1\n| Oct record high C = 35.6\n| Nov record high C = 36.2\n| Dec record high C = 35.0\n|year record high C = 37.3\n| Jan high C = 30.8\n| Feb high C = 31.2\n| Mar high C = 32.2\n| Apr high C = 33.0\n| May high C = 32.6\n| Jun high C = 31.8\n| Jul high C = 31.5\n| Aug high C = 31.7\n| Sep high C = 31.9\n| Oct high C = 32.3\n| Nov high C = 32.1\n| Dec high C = 31.4\n| year high C = 31.9\n| Jan mean C = 27.1\n| Feb mean C = 27.3\n| Mar mean C = 27.9\n| Apr mean C = 28.6\n| May mean C = 28.6\n| Jun mean C = 28.0\n| Jul mean C = 27.7\n| Aug mean C = 27.9\n| Sep mean C = 27.9\n| Oct mean C = 28.1\n| Nov mean C = 28.0\n| Dec mean C = 27.5\n| year mean C = 27.9\n| Jan low C = 23.3\n| Feb low C = 23.3\n| Mar low C = 23.6\n| Apr low C = 24.2\n| May low C = 24.6\n| Jun low C = 24.2\n| Jul low C = 23.9\n| Aug low C = 24.0\n| Sep low C = 23.9\n| Oct low C = 23.9\n| Nov low C = 23.9\n| Dec low C = 23.7\n| year low C = 23.9\n| Jan record low C = 17.0\n| Feb record low C = 16.1\n| Mar record low C = 17.4\n| Apr record low C = 19.1\n| May record low C = 20.2\n| Jun record low C = 20.3\n| Jul record low C = 20.0\n| Aug record low C = 18.5\n| Sep record low C = 20.0\n| Oct record low C = 19.2\n| Nov record low C = 19.1\n| Dec record low C = 16.2\n|year record low C = 16.1\n| Jan rain mm = 140.3\n| Feb rain mm = 109.4\n| Mar rain mm = 108.4\n| Apr rain mm = 124.7\n| May rain mm = 158.7\n| Jun rain mm = 186.7\n| Jul rain mm = 165.0\n| Aug rain mm = 170.0\n| Sep rain mm = 170.4\n| Oct rain mm = 174.8\n| Nov rain mm = 138.1\n| Dec rain mm = 112.6\n|year rain mm = 1759.1\n| rain colour = green\n| unit rain days = 0.1 mm\n| Jan rain days = 14\n| Feb rain days = 12\n| Mar rain days = 11\n| Apr rain days = 11\n| May rain days = 16\n| Jun rain days = 18\n| Jul rain days = 16\n| Aug rain days = 15\n| Sep rain days = 15\n| Oct rain days = 16\n| Nov rain days = 16\n| Dec rain days = 14\n|year rain days = 174\n| Jan humidity = 82\n| Feb humidity = 81\n| Mar humidity = 78\n| Apr humidity = 77\n| May humidity = 80\n| Jun humidity = 82\n| Jul humidity = 83\n| Aug humidity = 82\n| Sep humidity = 82\n| Oct humidity = 81\n| Nov humidity = 82\n| Dec humidity = 81\n| year humidity = 81\n| source 1 = [[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration|PAGASA]]<ref name=PAGASAnormals>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181002033257/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasanormvaldavdelsur1981-2010.csv\n| archivedate = 2 October 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-normal-values/resource/d9212dc8-8164-44ae-8170-cf3a306c7d82\n| title = Davao City, Davao del Sur Climatological Normal Values\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 1 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=PAGASAextremes>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181002033407/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasaclimextrdavcitydavdelsur.csv\n| archivedate = 2 October 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-extremes/resource/f35bb79e-e78b-4316-94c5-73ac6b09cbe5\n| title = Davao City, Davao del Sur Climatological Extremes\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 1 October 2018}}</ref>\n| date     = January 2013}}\n\n===Flora and fauna===\nMount Apo is home to many bird species, 111 of which are [[Endemism|endemic]] to the area. It is also home to one of the world's largest eagles, the [[critically endangered]] [[Philippine eagle]], the country's national bird. The Philippine Eagle Foundation is based near the city.<ref>{{cite web|title=Philippine Eagle Foundation|url=http://www.philippineeaglefoundation.org/philippine-eagle-center|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref> Plant species include the orchid ''[[waling-waling]]'', also known as the \"Queen of Philippine Flowers\" as well as one of the country's [[National symbols of the Philippines|national flower]]s, which are also endemic to the area. Fruits such as [[mangosteen]] (known as the \"queen of fruits\") and [[durian]] (known as the \"king of fruits\"), grow abundantly on Mount Apo. {{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Geology===\nDespite Davao City's location in the Asian portion of the Pacific [[Ring of Fire]], the city has suffered few earthquakes and most have been minor. [[Mount Apo]], {{convert|40|km}} southwest from the city proper, is a [[dormant volcano]].\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Philippine Census \n| align= none\n| title = Population census of Davao City\n| 1903 = \n| 1918 = \n| 1939 = \n| 1948 = \n| 1960 = \n| 1970 = 392473\n| 1975 = \n| 1980 = 614124\n| 1985 = 724935\n| 1990 = 849947\n| 1995 = 1006840\n| 2000 = 1147116\n| 2007 = 1363337\n| 2010 = 1449296\n| 2015 = 1632991\n| footnote = Source: [[Philippine Statistics Authority]]{{PH census|2015}}{{PH census|2010}}{{PH census|2007}}{{LWUA population data}} \n}}\n\nThe population of Davao City is 1,632,991 according to the 2015 census.{{PH census|2015}} [[Metro Davao]], with the city as its center, had about 2.5 million inhabitants in 2015, making it the [[Cities of the Philippines#Metropolitan areas|third-most-populous metropolitan area]] in the Philippines and the most-populous city in Mindanao. In 1995, the city's population reached 1,006,840 inhabitants, becoming the first city in Mindanao and the Visayas and the fourth nationwide to exceed one million inhabitants. The city's population increase during the 20th century was due to massive immigration waves coming from other parts of the nation and the trend continues to this day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/242629/davao-now-most-populous-urban-area-after-metro-manila |title=Davao now most populous urban area after Metro Manila |publisher= }}</ref> It is projected to surpass [[Manila]]'s population by 2020<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2015/09/18/1501296/philippine-cities-over-1m-population-nearly-triple-2025 |title=Philippine cities with over 1M population to nearly triple by 2025 |last= |first= |date=September 18, 2015 |work=Philippine Star |access-date=April 11, 2018}}</ref> to become the second-largest city in the Philippines.\n\n===Ethnicities===\n[[File:Bagobo woman.jpg|thumb|170px|left|alt=A Matigsalug woman in a red decorated tribal blouse making tribal bracelets|A Matigsalug woman]]\nResidents of Davao City and the whole corresponding Davao Region are colloquially known as ''[[Davaoe\u00f1o people|Davaoe\u00f1os]]''. Nearly all local Davaoe\u00f1os are [[Visayans]] (the majority are [[Cebuano people|Cebuanos]], with the rest being [[Hiligaynon people|Hiligaynons]]), while others of different ethnicities collectively categorized as the [[Lumad]]<nowiki/>s make up the remainder of the local population. The [[Moro people|Moro]] groups of the city are the [[Maguindanao people|Maguindanaons]], [[Maranao people|Maranaos]], [[Iranun]]s, [[Taus\u016bg people|Tausugs]] and the [[Sama-Bajau peoples|Sama-Bajaus]]. Non-Filipino Asians such as [[Indonesians]], [[Malaysians]], [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]], [[Chinese Filipinos]], [[Koreans in the Philippines#Davao|Koreans]], [[Japanese settlement in the Philippines|Japanese]] and [[Indian Filipinos|Indians]] have settled and made small communities in Davao City. Non-Asian foreigners such as the Americans and Europeans are also present in the city. {{citation needed|date=July 2017}}.\n\n===Languages===\n[[Cebuano language#Davaoe\u00f1o Cebuano|Cebuano]] is the most widely used language in the city and its satellite cities and towns. [[Philippine English|English]] is the medium of instruction in schools and is widely understood by residents, who often use it in varying professional fields. Aside from Cebuano, [[Chavacano#Castellano Abakay|Chavacano]] and [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]] are also widely used in addition to languages indigenous to the city, such as the [[Giangan language|Giangan]], the [[Kalagan language|Kalagan]], the [[Tagabawa language|Tagabawa]], the [[Matigsalug language|Matigsalug]], the [[Ata Manobo language|Ata Manobo]], and the [[Obo language|Obo]]. Other languages spoken in the city include [[Maguindanao language|Maguindanao]], [[Maranao language|Maranao]], [[Sama-Bajau languages|Sama-Bajau]], [[Iranun language|Iranun]] and [[Tausug language|Tausug]], followed by East Asian languages such as [[Philippine Hokkien|Hokkien]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and [[Korean language|Korean]].\n\n===Religion===\n[[File:San Pedro Cathedral 01.jpg|thumb|The city's San Pedro Cathedral]]\nThe majority of Davao City's inhabitants are [[Roman Catholics]] comprising 80% of the population. Other groups, such as the [[Iglesia ni Cristo]], Miracle Crusade, Pentecostal Missionary Church of Christ (4th Watch) and followers of the Kingdom of Jesus Christ, comprise eighteen percent of the city's religious background.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.davaopropertyfinder.com/about-davao-city/#religion|title=Davao City \u2013 Davao Property Finder|work=Davao Property Finder|access-date=2017-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Seventh-day Adventist]]s, the [[United Church of Christ in the Philippines]], [[Philippine Independent Church]] and [[Baptist]]s are the other Christian denominations. The remaining two percent belong to non-Christian faiths, mainly [[Islam]]. Some of the other faiths are [[Sikhism]], [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[animism]], [[Judaism]] and the non-religious.\n\nThe [[Restorationism (Christian primitivism)|Restorationist]] Church [[Kingdom of Jesus Christ (church)|Kingdom of Jesus Christ]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabreza |first1=Vincent |last2=Demetillo |first2=Donna |title=Couple who tried to free daughter from cult jailed |newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=August 26, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Dacanay |first=Barbara Mae |url=http://gulfnews.com/news/world/philippines/arroyo-welcomes-cult-leader-s-poll-support-1.621899 |title=Arroyo welcomes cult leader's poll support |work=gulfnews.com |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Padillo |first=Maya M |title=Villar is my mother's choice, says Quiboloy |url=http://www.dailymirror.ph/Mar-2010/Mar2010/front1.html |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |newspaper=The Mindanao Daily Mirror |date=March 20, 2010}}</ref> had its origins in the city. [[Apollo Quiboloy]], who claims to be the \"Appointed Son of God\", is the leader of the movement.\n\nThe [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Davao]] is the main metropolitan see of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in southern Mindanao. It comprises the city of Davao, the [[Island Garden City of Samal]] and the municipality of [[Talaingod, Davao del Norte|Talaingod]] in [[Davao del Norte province|Davao del Norte]]; under its jurisdiction are the three [[suffragan diocese]]s of [[Digos]], [[Tagum]] and [[Mati, Davao Oriental|Mati]] (the capital cities of the three Davao provinces). [[Archbishop]] [[Romulo Valles]] of the Archdiocese of Davao, appointed on February 11, 2012, by [[Pope Benedict XVI]], took office on May 22, 2012, at San Pedro Cathedral. [[Saint Peter]], locally known as ''San Pedro'', is the patron saint of the city.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Davao GMall 02.jpg|alt=|left|thumb|The Peak, Gaisano Mall]]\nDavao is part of the [[BIMP-EAGA|East Asian Growth Area]], a regional economic-cooperation initiative in [[Southeast Asia]].\n\nAccording to the foundation, the city has a projected average annual growth of 2.53 percent over a 15-year period; Davao was the only Philippine city to reach the top 100.<ref>[https://archive.today/20120911060237/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/local-news/2011/11/10/davao-worlds-87th-top-city-189867 Davao is world's 87th top city] \u2013 Sunstar Davao</ref> As the largest economy outside [[Metro Manila]], the city also serves as the largest local economy in southern Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/dcipc/newsimages/davaocityeconomicsituationer201220130724141409.pdf |title=DAVAO CITY ECONOMIC SITUATIONER 2012 |access-date=2015-01-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212849/http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/dcipc/newsimages/davaocityeconomicsituationer201220130724141409.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Industry===\nAgriculture remains the largest economic sector comprising banana, [[pineapple]], [[coffee]] and coconut plantations in the city. It is the island's leading exporter of fruits such as [[mango]]es, [[pomelo]]es, bananas, coconut products, pineapples, [[papaya]]s, [[Purple mangosteen|mangosteen]]s and [[Cocoa bean|cacao]].\n\nThe chocolate industry is the newest development in the city. Malagos Chocolate, developed here by Malagos Agriventures Corp., is now the country's leading artisan chocolate recognized worldwide. On the other hand, Seed Core Enterprises is the country's biggest exporter of [[Cocoa bean|cacao]] to [[Barry Callebaut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/48811-cacao-champion-dumaguete-chocolate|title=His cacao produces among the world's best chocolates|publisher=}}</ref> Durian which is locally grown and harvested in the city, is also a notable export, although banana is the largest fruit export in the city. Local corporations like Lorenzo Group, Anflo Group, AMS Group, Sarangani Agricultural Corp. and Vizcaya Plantations Inc. have operations and headquarters here. Multinational companies like [[Dole Food Company|Dole]], Sumifru/Sumitomo and [[Del Monte Foods|Del Monte]] have their regional headquarters here also.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/mobile/doc/62081689/List-of-Filipino-Banana-Growers|title=Archived copy|accessdate=2017-09-09|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118154847/https://www.scribd.com/mobile/doc/62081689/List-of-Filipino-Banana-Growers|archivedate=2017-01-18}}</ref>\n[[File:DavaoSkyline.jpg|thumb|239x239px|Abreeza Ayala Business District \u2013 one of the most prominent business centers in the city.]]\nThe [[Davao Gulf]] provides livelihood for many fishermen. Some of the fish products include yellow fin tuna, brackish water milkfish, mudfish, shrimp and crab.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destinationmindanaw.com/davao-del-norte/|title=Destination Mindanaw|access-date=2014-08-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821053312/http://www.destinationmindanaw.com/davao-del-norte/|archive-date=2014-08-21|url-status=dead}}</ref> Most of the fish catches are discharged in the fishing port in Barangay Toril, which are then sold in the numerous markets within the city.\n\nThe city also serves as the main trade, commerce, and industry hub of Mindanao and is also one of the financial hubs of Mindanao. [[Phoenix Petroleum]] is a multinational oil company based in Davao City and is the first company based outside [[Metro Manila]] to be in the [[PSE Composite Index]]. Several industrial plants such as those of Coca-Cola Bottlers, Phil., Pepsi-Cola Products, Phil., Interbev Phil Inc. and RC Cola Phil., companies are located in the city. There is also a number of fruit packaging-exporting facilities, and food manufacturing plants as well as industrial construction plants such as Holcim Philippines, Union Galvasteel Corporation, and SteelAsia. The SteelAsia plant is now the largest and most modern steel rolling mill production facility in the country, completed in December 2014<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/industries/208-infrastructure/77006-steelasia-completes-plant-davao-city|title=SteelAsia completes P3B plant in Davao City|work=Rappler}}</ref> and was purposely built to increase the national steel production and to reduce the construction costs in Mindanao.\n\n===Commerce===\n[[BDO Network Bank]] (formerly One Network Bank) is based in Davao City and is the largest rural bank in the Philippines in terms of assets. Most of its branches are located in Mindanao (including 17 locations where it is the only financial-services provider). Government social-insurance agencies such as the [[Social Security System (Philippines)|Social Security System]] and [[Government Service Insurance System (Philippines)|Government Service Insurance System]] also have locations in the city.\n\n[[File:Front facade of SM Lanang Premier, December 2012.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Front of large store, with cars in foreground|[[SM Lanang Premier]], the 2nd largest [[SM Supermall]] in [[Mindanao]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2012/04/18/world-class-sm-lanang-premier-reshaping-malling-mindanao-216858,|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304081253/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2012/04/18/world-class-sm-lanang-premier-reshaping-malling-mindanao-216858,|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-04|title=Business}}</ref>]]There are several commercial areas in the city: the city's downtown area, also known as the city centre, Davao Chinatown (Uyanguren), Bajada, Lanang, Matina, Ecoland, Agdao, Buhangin, Tibungco, Toril, Mintal and [[Calinan]], the latter three located at the southwestern part of the city.\n\nThere are many shopping centers that dot the city. Notable ones include: [[Gaisano Mall of Davao]], which opened in April 1997, is the largest Gaisano Mall in the Philippines,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davaochamber.com/membership-directory/gaisano-mall-of-davao/|title=Gaisano Mall of Davao &#124; DCCCII Membership|publisher=Davaochamber.com|date=2014-12-05|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> [[Abreeza]], which opened on May 12, 2011, is the first and largest [[Ayala Malls|Ayala Mall]] in Mindanao, and [[SM Lanang Premier]] which is the first SM Premier Mall in Mindanao.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.inquirer.net/84356/sm-group-to-open-biggest-shopping-mall-in-mindanao|title=SM group to open biggest shopping mall in Mindanao|first=Doris C.|last=Dumlao|publisher=}}</ref> Other major malls in the city include NCCC Mall of Davao, and [[SM City Davao|SM City Ecoland]], which is the first SM Mall in Mindanao<ref>{{cite web|author=Time to read less than 1 minute|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/feature/2017/11/18/sm-city-davao-turns-16-575225|title=SM City Davao turns 16|publisher=SunStar|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> among many others. [[Victoria Plaza Mall]], located on J.P. Laurel Ave., is the oldest shopping mall in the city, established in 1992. Felcris Centrale<ref>{{cite web|title = Felcris Centrale \u2013 Building for Rent or Sale {{!}} KMC MAG Group Inc.|url = http://kmcmaggroup.com/building/Felcris-Centrale/|website = kmcmaggroup.com|accessdate = 2015-12-28}}</ref> is a mixed use Retail Mall, supermarket, and IT office complex located along Quimpo Boulevard. Gaisano Mall of Toril, which is the second Gaisano Mall under the DSG Sons Group in the city, is a large shopping mall located in Toril District at the southern part of the city. Some minor malls/community malls include Gaisano Grand Tibungco, NCCC Panacan, NCCC Main Uyanguren, Gaisano Grand Calinan, Gaisano Grand Ilustre, and Gaisano Grand Toril. Construction of new shopping malls in the city are currently underway. Gaisano Grand Citygate Mall,<ref>{http://southerndc.blogspot.com/2012/06/js-gaisano-grand-buhangin.html}}</ref> which is the fifth Gaisano Mall in the city under the Gaisano Grand Group, is a large shopping mall being constructed in Buhangin District just a few kilometers north of the downtown area. NCCC Mall Buhangin,<ref>{http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2015/06/16/another-nccc-mall-rise-buhangin-413584}}</ref> is the second NCCC Mall in the city which is also located in Buhangin District just beside Gaisano Grand Mall Buhangin. There are also proposed malls which include CityMall Northtown Davao,<ref>{http://www.doubledragon.com.ph/article/citymall-to-rise-at-northtown-davao}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which will be the first CityMall in the city that will rise in a 1.5 hectare lot within the vicinity of Northtown, a 116-hectare residential estate by the Alsons Dev. in Barangay Cabantian, Davao City, and the Vista Mall Davao,<ref>{http://bworldonline.com/vista-land-ventures-mixed-use-development-davao-city/}}</ref> which will rise in Tugbok District.\n\n==Culture and heritage==\n\n===Foreign influence===\n[[File:Chinatown Davao City.jpg|thumb|Davao City's Chinatown is said to be the Philippines' biggest in terms of land area.]]\nAs with most cities in the Philippines, Christianity is widespread as a result of Spanish colonialism. Christian churches and chapels dot the city's landscape. A small number of temples, mosques and other religions' places of worship may also be found around the city.\n\nA notable tradition brought by the Spanish still celebrated today in Davao City is the celebration of the feast day of each of the [[barrio]]s (villages) patron saints with a [[festival]] (''fiesta''). These are celebrated through song and dance.\n\nThe biggest celebration native to the city is the [[Kadayawan Festival]] in early to mid August which, in pre-colonial times was a celebration of the harvest. Today, it serves to commemorate the cultures of the indigenous tribes that inhabit the area surrounding Davao City. Many tribes people visit the city during this time. Festivities include native Mindanaoan street dances, motorcades featuring various clubs and social awareness groups based in the city and art exhibits in various locations featuring local artists and artisans.\n\nThe [[Davao Chinatown]] is the primary residence of the Chinese community in the city. It has its own seaport, the Santa Ana Wharf, which is also a part of [[Port of Davao|Davao International Port]].\n\n[[Japanese culture|Japanese cultural influence]], like that of the Chinese, was also prominent in the city. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}} The Japanese Community was concentrated in Mintal in the 3rd District of Toril, Davao City. In fact, a Japanese cemetery and Japanese Shrine is located there in Bago Oshiro in Mintal. Evidence of Japanese influence is still visible in Bago Oshiro where there are Japanese villages and schools. There are various Japanese-owned businesses in the city as well. Davao City is also home to Philippine Nikkei Jin Kai International School, a Japanese-administered educational institution.\n\nSeveral foreign communities reside in the city, including Indonesians, Malaysians, Koreans and Indians. There are [[ESL]] schools for foreigners, and export-oriented industrial parks to entice Japanese and (South) Korean firms to set up shop in the city. However, there has been some cultural conflict over the integration of Koreans in the city, with then-city mayor Rodrigo Duterte complaining about their habit of smoking in public places.<ref>{{citation |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view/20070902-86154/Davao_City_mayor_frowns_on_Koreans%92_smoking_in_public_places |periodical=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=2007-09-02 |accessdate=2011-05-22 |last=Tupas |first=Jeffrey M.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904151305/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view_article.php?article_id=86154 |archivedate=2007-09-04|title=Davao City mayor frowns on Koreans' smoking in public places}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|Heritage sites}}Heritage===\nThere are a number of cultural-heritage sites in the city, including the Davao Museum (in Insular Village, Lanang), the Mindanao Folk Arts Museum (Philippine Women's College, Juna Subdivision, Matina), Davaoe\u00f1o Historical Society Museum (at Magallanes and Claveria Streets) and the Philippine-Japan Museum (Matsuo Compound, Calinan). Japanese historical sites include the Japanese Tunnel (used by Japanese forces during World War II), the 20th-century Japanese cemetery and the Furukawa Fiber Plant (used by Yoshizo Furukawa as an abac\u00e1 and banana plantation).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://davaotoday.com/sections/guide/museums.php|title=Fair. In-Depth. Relevant|publisher=Davao Today|accessdate=2012-11-07|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120730034508/http://davaotoday.com/sections/guide/museums.php|archivedate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===Cuisine===\n[[File:Ginanggang.jpg|thumb|alt=Four grilled bananas on wooden sticks|''[[Ginanggang]]'', grilled [[saba banana]]s with margarine and brushed with sugar, originated in Davao.]]\nThe cuisine of Davao City features skewered and grilled meat dishes, but the most common dish served in the city is [[kinilaw]], a relative of [[ceviche]] made from [[tuna]], [[mackerel]], or [[swordfish]] with [[cucumber]] (and sometimes [[radish]]es) and [[chili pepper|chili]] marinated in vinegar. ''Sinuglaw'', a portmanteau of ''sinugba'' (grilled) and ''kinilaw'' in the Cebuano language, is also a term for a dish in which diced, grilled pork belly is mixed with ''kinilaw''.\n\nFruit dishes, snacks, and desserts are also popular, most made from durian and bananas. ''[[Ginanggang]]'' is a banana dish that originated in this city and spread to other parts of the country; a banana is grilled, skewered, brushed with margarine and sprinkled with sugar. [[Durian]] also made appearance on Davao's culinary scene.\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Land of Promise 2.jpg|thumb|left|Land of Promise, located atop a hill at The Gap Farming Resort]]\n{{Wikivoyage}}\nThe [[Philippine eagle]], the country's national bird and considered the largest eagle in the world, is endemic to Davao.<ref>{{cite web |title=Philippine Eagle: The largest Eagle In The World |url=http://dinoanimals.com/animals/philippine-eagle-the-largest-eagle-in-the-world/ |publisher=DinoAnimals.com |accessdate=October 8, 2016 |date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> The orchid ''[[Euanthe sanderiana|waling-waling]]'' and fruits such as durians, marang, rambutans, pomeloes and mangosteens are popular and generally cheaper in the city. Tourist destinations in the city include the Philippine Eagle Foundation and Nature Center, [[Mount Apo]], Gap Farming Resort, the Davao Crocodile Park, Malagos Garden Resort, Eden Nature Park, and [[People's Park (Davao City)|People's Park]] in the city center which is popular for its sculptures of indigenous people and dancing fountain. [[Samal, Davao del Norte|Samal Island]], a part of [[Metro Davao]], is an island city situated immediately off the city's coast in the Davao Gulf, popularly known for its scenic beaches.\n\nTwo major annual festivals are held in the city: the ''Araw ng Dabaw'' (Day of Davao) on March 16 (The city's incorporation day) and the [[Kadayawan Festival]] in August.<ref>{{cite web |title=Davao City: Treasures and Pleasures from Islands to Highlands |url=http://www.choosephilippines.com/specials/lists/929/davao-city-treasures-pleasures-islands-highlands/ |publisher=ChoosePhilippines |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |date=August 12, 2013}}</ref> Also celebrated in the entire month of December, Pasko Fiesta sa Davao is an integration of festive and competitive Christmas activities showcasing colorful lightings and array of decorations in barangays, public parks, roads and buildings, and a series of competitive performances. Another annual festival, the [[Davao City Torotot Festival|Torotot Festival]],<ref name=\"colina\">Colina, Antonio IV. [https://archive.today/20140323181407/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/weekend-davao/2014/01/04/torotot-festival-celebrating-new-year-safest-way-321581 \"Torotot Festival: Celebrating New Year the safest way\"] ''[[Sun.Star|Sun Star]]'', Davao City, 4 January 2014. Retrieved on 10 January 2014.</ref> is held annually every New Year's Eve. First organized in the last day of 2013 during the 2014 New Year's Eve, it was organized as a recompense for the city firecracker-pyrotechnics ban; it includes a number of people simultaneously blowing party horns, locally known as ''torotots''. It recorded a number of 7,568 people<ref name = \"tacio\">Tacio, Henrylito. [http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/342004/lifestyle/peopleandevents/safe-from-firecrackers-davao-sets-torotot-record-instead \"Safe from firecrackers, Davao sets torotot record instead\u2019] \u2018\u2019[[GMA News Online]]'', Davao City, 1 January 2014. Retrieved on 10 January 2014.</ref> participating in the first event, aiming to break the world record set by Japan for the most people simultaneously blowing party horns.\n\nDuring 2011, there were 1,075,000 recorded tourist arrivals in the city, totaled from 81,081 foreign travelers, 983,315 local citizens, and 10,604 balikbayans/overseas Filipino workers. Estimated tourist receipts were recorded at 12.81 billion pesos while estimated economic benefits were 28.19 billion pesos.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/dcipc/newsimages/davaocityeconomicsituationer201220130724141409.pdf |title=DAVAO CITY ECONOMIC SITUATIONER 2012 Tourism Section |access-date=2015-01-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923212849/http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/dcipc/newsimages/davaocityeconomicsituationer201220130724141409.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Government==\n[[File:Commemorative Monument of Peace & Unity.JPG|thumb|alt=Statue of people and doves|Commemorative Monument of Peace and Unity, with the Legislative Building in the background]]\n\nDavao City is currently governed by the city mayor [[Sara Duterte|\"Inday\" Sara Duterte]], daughter of the Philippine president [[Rodrigo Duterte|Rodrigo \"Roa\" Duterte]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ranada|first=Pia|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/politics/elections/2019/230511-davao-city-results-victory-for-all-dutertes|title=Victory for all 3 Duterte children in Davao City|date=May 13, 2019|work=Rappler|access-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The city also has a vice mayor in the person of Sebastian \"Baste\" Duterte, \"Inday\" Sara's brother, who ran unopposed during the last [[2019 Philippine gubernatorial elections]].\n\nDavao City has [[Barangays of Davao City|182 barangays]], with three legislative districts. The city government of Davao is proposing two more congressional districts to serve its growing population.\n\nMembers of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|House of Representatives]] are:\n*1st District: Paolo Duterte\n*2nd District: Vincent Garcia\n*3rd District: Isidro T. Ungab\n\n===Barangays===\n[[File:Ph fil Davao City districts.png|thumb|upright=1.1|{{center|'''Political map of Davao City districts'''}}]]\n{{See also|Districts of Davao City}}\nThe 182 barangays of Davao City is arranged according to the 3 legislative districts and 11 administrative districts of the city.\n\n=={{anchor|Accessibility and Transportation}}Transport==\n\n==={{anchor|By land}}Land===\n[[File:Quezon Boulevard Davao-c.JPG|thumb|right|Quezon Boulevard]]\nPopular modes of public transportation in the city are multicabs, [[jeepneys]], [[motorized tricycle|tricycles]], [[buses]] and [[taxi]]s. Multicabs and jeepneys ply 82 designated passenger-vehicle routes around the clock. Tricycles ply routes beyond the main streets of the city. Taxis have several routes in and around Davao City. In mountainous areas, the ''habal-habal'' passenger motorcycle is the main mode of transportation\n\nThe city has the first taxis in the Philippines to accept payments from [[BancNet]] and [[MegaLink]] ATM and debit cards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Davao Black Taxis sport tourism logos|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2012/08/27/davao-black-taxis-sport-tourism-logos-239661|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130615195723/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2012/08/27/davao-black-taxis-sport-tourism-logos-239661|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 15, 2013|newspaper=Davao Sun Star|date=August 27, 2012|accessdate=May 16, 2013}}</ref> The black taxis are linked to the [[Global Positioning System]] (GPS), and dispatching is done by computer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/07/06/12/davaos-black-taxis-go-hi-tech|title=Davao's black taxis go hi-tech|date=July 6, 2012|website=ABS-CBNnews.com|accessdate=May 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe city offers a wide bus network to cities and provinces in Mindanao and as far as [[Pasay]] in Luzon, and [[Ormoc]] and [[Tacloban]] in the Visayas. The city is accessible by bus from several points in Mindanao such as [[Cotabato City|Cotabato]], [[Kidapawan]], [[General Santos]], [[Digos]], [[Koronadal]], [[Isulan]], [[Tagum]], [[Tandag]], [[Bislig]], [[Malaybalay]], [[Mati, Davao Oriental|Mati]], [[Monkayo]], [[Malita, Davao Occidental|Malita]], [[Cagayan de Oro]], [[Butuan]], and [[Surigao City|Surigao]] .\n\nConstruction and improvement of roads and bridges in the city are underway. The city's third major road, the Buhangin Underpass, was completed in the first quarter of 2003. The Traffic Management and Computerization Scheme was implemented, considered one of the most modern in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindanews.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1565|title=Davao's new traffic system is \"Asia's most modern\"|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nA {{convert|28|km|adj=on}} monorail project, named the [[Davao People Mover]], has been endorsed by the City Government to the Department of Transportation and Communication (DOTC) and Philippine National Railways (PNR).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perez|first1=Ace June Rell S.|title=Davao City endorses monorail project|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/business/2015/10/21/davao-city-endorses-monorail-project-437144|accessdate=October 21, 2015|publisher=Sun Star|date=October 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA road project, expected to end by 2022, is aiming to reduce travel time from 1 hour and 44 minutes via Pan-Philippine Highway and Diversion Road to 49 minutes via Davao By\u2013pass road.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.build.gov.ph/Home/Project_Details/50?Agency=DPWH|title=Davao City By-pass\"|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==={{anchor|By sea}}Sea===\n[[File:Sasa Wharf-Davao.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Large ship approaching a wharf|The [[Port of Davao]] is the busiest port in Mindanao.]]\nDavao is connected to Manila by [[roll-on/roll-off]] inter-island ferries. The city is served by domestic passenger ferries at Sasa International Seaport and Santa Ana Wharf, the international seaports of the [[Port of Davao]], the busiest port in Mindanao.<ref name=\"Port of Davao\">{{cite web|url=http://customs.gov.ph/about/directory/directory-port-of-davao/|title=Directory Port of Davao|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106103501/http://customs.gov.ph/about/directory/directory-port-of-davao/|archivedate=2014-11-06}}</ref> The port is capable of servicing inter-island and international shipments. It is located in Davao Gulf and has two approaches, one at Pakiputan Strait between Davao and western [[Samal Island]].\n\nThe Davao City and General Santos to Bitung, Indonesia sea connectivity route has also had just been started very recently. {{When|date=May 2017}} This route will enable traders from Mindanao to easily export goods and commodities like food and beverage, electronics and garments, beauty products, fertilizer, construction materials, agricultural inputs, tin cans and packaging materials up to North Sulawesi in Indonesia. The roll-on-roll-off (Ro-Ro) shipping service which will serve the route is the Asian Marine Transport, a Philippine registered shipping firm and operator of the Super Shuttle Ferry, Super Shuttle Roro, and Shuttle Fast Ferry vessels.\n\n==={{anchor|By air}}Air===\n[[File:Davao International Airport.jpg|thumb|alt=White air-traffic control tower|Davao International Airport's [[air traffic control]] tower is considered the most advanced ATC in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.adb.org/Media/Articles/2006/10057-Philippines-Davao-airport/default.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705123339/http://www.adb.org/Media/Articles/2006/10057-Philippines-Davao-airport/default.asp|url-status=dead|title=Upgraded Davao City International Airport Is Ready for More Passengers and Bigger Aircraft|archive-date=July 5, 2009}}</ref>]]\nLocated north from the city center, [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport]] is the major airport serving the city and the region. It is the busiest airport in Mindanao and the third-busiest in the country. Around 1966, Philippine Airlines(PAL), the country's largest fleet and flag carrier, began its first domestic jet service. The airport handles flights to 9 domestic destinations and 5 international destinations, namely, [[Hong Kong]], [[Quanzhou]], [[Manado]], [[Singapore]], and the first ever long haul flight to and from Mindanao, which is [[Qatar Airways]]' [[Doha]]-[[Clark Freeport and Special Economic Zone|Clark]]-Davao-[[Doha]] flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/1810539|title=Qatar Airways launches Doha-Davao route|last=Perez|first=Ace June Rell S.|date=2019-06-18|website=Sunstar|language=English|access-date=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n==Utilities==\n[[Davao Light and Power Company]], an Aboitiz company which is the third-largest electric utility company in the country, serves the city's electricity needs. It had its own gas-operating power plant at Bajada district and 300-megawatt coal-fired power plant in Toril district.\n\nDavao City Water District is the main water supplier in the city. It taps its water supply from the mountain springs in the city's western portion as well as from underground or surface water sources. {{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} The city's water supply runs through the company's production wells, sumps and reservoirs within the city. Its biggest water supply system is located at Barangay Dumoy.\n\n==Health care==\nThere are 31 hospitals and tertiary centers in the city like the Davao Doctors Hospital, San Pedro Hospital, Brokenshire Memorial Hospital, Ricardo Limso Medical Center, Davao Medical School Foundation Hospital (DMSF Hospital), Metro Davao Medical and Research Center, Adventist Hospital, MMG Hospital, CHDC Hospital and the Southern Philippines Medical Center. In addition, [[CURE International]], a non-profit organization that operates charitable hospitals and programs worldwide, operates the [[CURE International#Tebow CURE Hospital|Tebow CURE Hospital]], which is an orthopedic specialty hospital located in Davao City. It provides elective surgeries to both children and adults. Their primary charitable mission is to heal disabled children with conditions such as clubfoot, bowed legs, other bone deformities, untreated burns and cleft lip.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KDdy6v__KUs|title=Tebow Opens Children's 'Palace of Healing'|publisher=CBN News|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDavao City is also noted and have been praised by the World Health Organization for its smoke-free policy since 2002.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://extranet.who.int/kobe_centre/en|title=WHO Kobe|website=WHO Kobe}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> the first in the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/206701/davao-city-lauded-for-smoking-ban|title=Davao City lauded for smoking ban|first=Philippine Daily|last=Inquirer|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref>\n\n==Law and order==\nLaw and order is maintained by the [[Philippine National Police]] and a special military group, Task Force (TF) Davao. TF Davao is formed to protect the city from terrorist attacks and other crime and is affiliated with the [[Philippine Army]] and headed by an army [[colonel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/1748643/Davao/Local-News/84-paramilitary-men-complete-training|title=84 paramilitary men complete training|first=Juliet C.|last=Revita|date=June 18, 2018|website=Sunstar}}</ref>\n\nA [[curfew]] on minors is enforced. All businesses, especially [[Bar (establishment)|bars]] and [[Nightclub|discos]], are mandated by a city ordinance to stop selling alcoholic drinks at 1:00&nbsp;am (Final approval last July 24, 2013). [[Motorcycle|Motorcyclists]] without helmets and motorists with defective lights are not legally allowed to enter (or drive in) the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/regions/07/25/13/davaos-liquor-ban-begin-1-am|title=Davao's liquor ban to begin at 1 a.m.|first=ABS-CBN|last=News|website=ABS-CBN News}}</ref> Executive Order No. 39 imposes the reduction of speed limits for all kinds of motor vehicles within the territorial jurisdiction of Davao City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/684841/davao-citys-speed-limit-reduces-accidents-but-businesses-also-affected|title=Davao City's speed limit reduces accidents, but businesses also affected|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|author=Mejos, A.I.|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nPresident [[Rodrigo Duterte]], mayor of Davao for a total of 22 years, has benefited from reports in the national media that he made Davao into one of the world's safest cities, and he cites this as justification for his [[Philippine Drug War|national drug policy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Duterte calls for press conference Monday afternoon|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2015/10/12/Duterte-press-conference-October-12.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=[[CNN Philippines]]|date=12 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rodrigo Duterte: The Rise of Philippines' Death Squad Mayor|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/07/17/rodrigo-duterte-rise-philippines-death-squad-mayor|accessdate=1 October 2017|publisher=Human Rights Watch|date=July 17, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160901200109/https://www.hrw.org/news/2015/07/17/rodrigo-duterte-rise-philippines-death-squad-mayor|archivedate=1 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Philippines' strongman president is losing popularity as citizens tire of drug war|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/10/philippines-drug-war-hits-president-rodrigo-duterte-popularity-ratings.html|accessdate=11 October 2017|publisher=CNBC|date=11 October 2017}}</ref> He has boasted that he made Davao into one of the world's safest cities by killing all of the criminals.<ref name=\"kill\">{{Cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/halalan2016/nation/regions/05/25/15/duterte-admits-links-davao-death-squad-says-hell-kill-100000-criminals |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-05-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185858/http://news.abs-cbn.com/halalan2016/nation/regions/05/25/15/duterte-admits-links-davao-death-squad-says-hell-kill-100000-criminals |archive-date=2018-06-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, raw data from the Philippine National Police for the years 2010 to 2015 shows that the city had the highest murder rate in the Philippines, the second highest number of rapes, and the fourth highest number of index crimes.<ref name=\"g\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/02/philippines-president-duterte-drugs-war-death-squads|title=Thousands dead: the Philippine president, the death squad allegations and a brutal drugs war|date=2 April 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 September 2017|quote=claims of having established law and order in Davao... But behind the bluster the statistics don\u2019t lie}}</ref><ref name=\"op\">{{cite news|title=Hits and misses: Fact checking Trillanes on Davao City|url=http://old.philstar.com/headlines/2018/02/13/1787474/hits-and-misses-fact-checking-trillanes-davao-city|accessdate=18 February 2018|work=Philippine Star|date=13 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218210320/http://old.philstar.com/headlines/2018/02/13/1787474/hits-and-misses-fact-checking-trillanes-davao-city|archive-date=18 February 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Davao City Council officially declared Senator [[Antonio Trillanes]] \"''[[persona non grata]]''\" after video emerged of him citing the police data to debunk the claim of Davao being the world's safest city, which he said that Davaoenos were \"brainwashed\" into believing. He said that he was \"expressing what Davaoenos cannot express out of fear.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Trillanes unperturbed by 'persona non grata' tag|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/02/13/trillanes-unperturbed-by-persona-non-grata-tag/|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=Manila Bulletin|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Trillanes declared persona non grata in Davao City|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/02/13/trillanes-declared-persona-non-grata-in-davao-city/|accessdate=19 February 2018|work=Manila Bulletin|date=13 February 2018}}</ref> Media claims of \"safest city\" often cite rankings from [[Numbeo]], a [[crowd-sourced]] survey website; as of February 2018, Davao had dropped to 275th out of 330 cities in Numbeo's \"crime index\".<ref name=\"n1\">{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/690252/davao-city-ranks-as-9th-safest-in-the-world|title=Davao City ranks as 9th safest in the world|first=Philippine Daily|last=Inquirer|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref><ref name=\"n2\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/125132/davao-city-improves-to-5th-in-ranking-of-worlds-safest-cities|title=Davao City improves to 5th in ranking of world's safest cities|first=Aries Joseph|last=Hegina|website=globalnation.inquirer.net}}</ref><ref name=\"n3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/16007/Business/Davao-now-4th-safest-city|title=Davao now 4th safest city|first=Ruji Peter S.|last=Abat|date=June 24, 2015|website=Sunstar}}</ref><ref name=op/>\n\nThe Public Safety and Security Command Center (PSSCC), the first in the Philippines, is located in Sandawa, Matina. It is headquarters for [[9-1-1 (Philippines)|911]] and the center for the 170 closed-circuit television (CCTV) cameras installed in different strategic areas as of today covering access roads and populated downtown areas, and also including outside the Davao International Airport and six in different bridges to monitor the rise of water level in the city's rivers. The center also controls traffic signals in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2013/06/davao-goes-high-tech-on-public-safety-security-efforts/|title=Davao goes high-tech on public safety, security efforts|date=June 7, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Davao, by city ordinance, police ensure that prostitutes have a valid health card, but do not arrest them.<ref>{{cite news|title=Welcome to Davao, the Philippine Leader's Town: 'No Smoking, No Crime'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/17/world/asia/philippines-davao-duterte.html|accessdate=8 October 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=16 June 2016}}</ref> In 2010, the Philippine Child Protection Unit stated that Davao was one of the top five areas in the Philippines for [[child prostitution]] and [[sex tourism]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Children and the sex trade|url=http://www.edgedavao.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=24155:children-and-the-sex-trade-first-of-two-parts&catid=60:special-feature&Itemid=85|accessdate=8 October 2016|work=Edge Davao|date=26 December 2015}}</ref> Jeanette Ampog, the executive director of [https://web.archive.org/web/20170101091334/http://talikala.net/ Talikala], a Davao-based [[NGO]] that helps prostitutes, said in October 2016 that child prostitution had sharply increased over the past two years. She said that children were cheaper and more marketable.<ref>{{cite news|title=Child prostitution in Davao rising|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/davao/local-news/2016/10/04/child-prostitution-davao-rising-501485|accessdate=8 October 2016|work=Sun Star|date=4 October 2016}}</ref> Nevertheless, the city was awarded \"Most Child-Friendly City for Highly-Urbanized Category\" in 2013, 2014 and 2017. The city also won the same award in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Another child-friendly award given Davao|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/690922/another-child-friendly-award-given-davao|accessdate=26 July 2018|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=13 May 2015}}</ref> Also in 2017, the city was awarded with the \"Best Disaster Risk Reduction and Management\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Davao City bags Kalasag, Most Child-Friendly awards|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph/article/409592/Davao-City-bags-Kalasag-Most-Child-Friendly-awards|accessdate=26 July 2018|work=[[Sun.Star]]|date=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe city's Executive Order No. 04, Series of 2013 imposes an order on creating the implementation of rules and regulations for the new comprehensive anti-smoking ordinance no. 0367-12, Series of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philstar.com/nation/2014/02/13/1289610/noy-complies-davao-citys-smoking-ordinance|title=Noy complies with Davao City's smoking ordinance|newspaper=[[The Philippine Star]]|author=Regalado, E.|date=13 February 2014|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref> Davao City's [[Firecracker#Firecracker ban|Firecracker Ban]] was also implemented with ordinance No. 060-02/1406-02, Series of 2002.<ref name=\"cnnphdvo\">{{cite web|url=http://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/05/17/davao-city-ordinances.html|title=Davao City ordinances that may be implemented nationwide under a Duterte presidency|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|author=Tordecilla, K.|date=18 May 2016|accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 and 2017, Davao City is among the local government units awarded with a \"Seal of Good Local Governance\" by the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dilg.gov.ph/PDF_File/reports_resources/dilg-reports-resources-20161027_8441b747a6.pdf|title=''DILG Official SGLG Report 2016''}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dilg.gov.ph/PDF_File/reports_resources/dilg-reports-resources-2017118_0448ec1740.pdf|title=''DILG Officil SGLG Report 2017''}}</ref> The city was also given the same award in 2015, prior to the presidency of Rodrigo Duterte.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dilg.gov.ph/PDF_File/reports_resources/dilg-reports-resources-2015915_f05b70a93d.pdf|title=''DILG Official SGLG Report 2015''}}</ref>\n\n===Davao Death Squad===\n{{Main|Davao Death Squad}}\nThe [[Davao Death Squad]] is a [[vigilante]] group supposedly active in Davao City. The group is allegedly responsible for [[summary execution]]s of [[Street children in the Philippines|street children]] and individuals suspected of petty crimes and dealing in drugs in Davao.<ref name=\"Human Rights Watch\">{{cite web|title=\"You Can Die Any Time\" Death Squad Killings in Mindanao|url=https://www.hrw.org/sites/default/files/reports/philippines0409webwcover_0.pdf|website=www.hrw.org|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> It has been estimated that the group is responsible for the killing or disappearance of between 1,020 and 1,040 people between 1998 and 2008.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite web|title=Philippine death squads extend their reach|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/22/world/asia/22iht-phils.html?_r=0|website=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"www.news.com.au\">{{cite web|title=The Philippines' real-life Punisher, Davao City Mayor Rodrigo Duterte, urged to run for president|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/asia/the-philippines-reallife-punisher-davao-city-mayor-rodrigo-duterte-urged-to-run-for-president/story-fnh81fz8-1226973937374|website=[[News.com.au]]|publisher=|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> In as early as 2005, the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] has received reports of the [[Human rights commission|Human Rights Commission]]'s (HRC) investigation regarding the alleged connection of the [[Rodrigo Duterte|Duterte]] political dynasty of Davao to the killings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/05MANILA312_a.html|title=MORE VIGILANTE-STYLE KILLINGS REPORTED IN DAVAO CITY|last=|first=|date=20 January 2005|website=Wikileaks|accessdate=}}</ref> This was followed by another investigation in 2009, which was later discontinued.<ref>{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=8 May 2009|title=Davao Officials Deny Vigilante Killings, but Human Rights Commission Blames Mayor|url=https://search.wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/09MANILA1002_a.html|journal=|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Another investigation by the [[Office of the Ombudsman of the Philippines|Office of the Ombudsman]] was opened and closed in 2019, stating that they found no evidence that the alleged group exists.<ref name=\"Reuters-DeathSquads\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-philippines-duterte-killings-insight-idUSKCN0YG0EB|title=Philippine death squads very much in business as Duterte set for presidency|last1=Marshall|first1=Andrew R.C.|date=May 26, 2016|work=Reuters|accessdate=December 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526131335/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-philippines-duterte-killings-insight-idUSKCN0YG0EB|archivedate=May 26, 2016|last2=Mogato|first2=Manuel}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{See also|List of colleges and universities in Davao City}}\n[[File:UP Mindanao SOM Building.jpg|thumb|250px|[[University of the Philippines Mindanao]]]]\nThe city government provides free education at the primary (grade school) and secondary (high school) levels at public institutions. Currently, as sanctioned by the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]], all primary and secondary institutions in the city use the [[K\u201312 (education)|K-12]] educational system. The city currently hosts five universities.\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:Davao City Sports Complex UP.jpg|thumb|300px|The stadium and track-and-field area of [[Davao City\u2013UP Sports Complex|Davao City Sports Complex]].]]\n[[File:Cock Fight Arina Davao.jpg|thumb|''[[Sabong]]'' or cockfight in Davao City.|left]]\nSports facilities in the city include the Davao City Recreation Center (Almendras Gymnasium), Tionko Football Field (near Agro College and the Davao River) and the gymnasiums of Ateneo de Davao University, Philippine Women's College of Davao's Rosa Santos Munda Events Center (RSM Events Center), the University of Southeastern Philippines, Holy Cross of Davao College, the University of Mindanao, and Mintal Comprehensive National High School. The main sports center of Davao City and also the largest is the [[Davao City\u2013UP Sports Complex|Davao City Sports Complex]], which hosted the [[2019 Palarong Pambansa|2019 National Games]].\n\nThere are locally based sports teams in the city. [[Davao F.A.|Davao Football Association]], working under the [[Philippine Football Federation]], represents the city and Davao Region for national [[association football|football]] events. Locally based basketball teams such as ''Goldstar Davao'' and ''Duterte Agilas'' work for the [[Mindanao Visayas Basketball Association]]. Collegiate varsity teams based in the tertiary institutions inside the city also compete in national competitions.\n\n[[Sabong]] or cockfighting events are also held in cockfighting arenas within the city. In June 2015, the city held the country's largest cockfighting event, the 6th Annual Thunderbird Challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mindanaotimes.net/top-breeders-show-wares-in-thunderbird-davao-challenge/|title=Top breeders show wares in Thunderbird Davao Challenge \u2013 Mindanao Times|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nSports management group [[Sonshine Sports Management]] is also based here.\n\n==Media==\nNational media networks such as [[GMA Network]], [[ABS-CBN]], [[TV5 (Philippines)|5]], [[People's Television Network|PTV]], [[Intercontinental Broadcasting Corporation|IBC]], and [[CNN Philippines]] maintain local stations in the city. The broadcast coverage of these media stations includes all of Davao Region as well as some areas beyond the region.\n\nThere are media networks based in the city as well. Davao Christian Broadcasting Channel and [[Sonshine Media Network International]] are two religion-oriented media networks, with the latter having a nationwide broadcast coverage as well as news & current affairs programs. The locally based community network [[SouthSpot]] broadcasts only on cable television.\n\nIn addition to 24 national newspapers, Davao City has 21 local daily newspapers, including the ''Sun Star Davao'', the city-based ''[[Mindanao Times]]'', and the ''[[Mindanao Examiner]]''.\n\nDavao City also invests in Online Media and has its official online news/media website which is the Davao Eagle.\n\n==Foreign relations==\nThe influx of foreign visitors and the presence of [[expatriates]] and [[Immigration|migrants]] in the city have prompted the governments of Japan, China, Malaysia, and [[Indonesia]] to open Consulates-General in the city, while Palau and the United States have consular offices. Honorary consulates of the Czech Republic, Mexico, Austria, Spain, Timor Leste, Denmark and South Korea were also recently established.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mzv.cz/manila/en/about_the_embassy/index.html|title=About the Embassy &#124; Embassy of the Czech Republic in Manila|publisher=Mzv.cz|date=|accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy3289/|title=Consulate of Mexico in Davao City, Philippines|publisher=Embassypages.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy21339/|title=Consulate of Austria in Davao City, Philippines|publisher=Embassypages.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy14379/|title=Consulate of Denmark in Davao City, Philippines|publisher=Embassypages.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy19700/|title=Consulate of Spain in Davao City, Philippines|publisher=Embassypages.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassypages.com/missions/embassy6342/|title=Consulate of Timor-Leste in Davao City, Philippines|publisher=Embassypages.com|date=|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> United States Embassy in the Philippines opened a virtual consulate, where inquiries regarding [[Visa (document)|visa]]s, foreign-relations concerns and travel to the United States can be made by [[e-mail]] and [[Online chat|chat]]. The virtual consulate is maintained in coordination with [[Ateneo de Davao University]], [[University of Mindanao]], [[University of the Immaculate Conception]], [[Holy Cross of Davao College]] and AMA Computer College.\n\n==Sister towns and cities==\nThere are 10 [[Twin towns and sister cities|sister cities]] of Davao, as designated by Sister Cities International (SCI):\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Local\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| style=\"vwidth:110%;\"|\n*[[Baguio]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baguiomidlandcourier.com.ph/city.asp?mode=%20archives/2009/september/9-6-2009/city6.txt|title=20 sister cities pledge to fortify ties with Baguio|newspaper=Baguio Midland Courier}}</ref>\n*[[Manila]]\n*[[Quezon City]], since {{date|October 12, 1994}}<ref name=\"QuezonCityGovPH-SisterCities\">{{cite web |title=Sister Cities |url=http://quezoncity.gov.ph/index.php/quezon-city-business-district/350-sister-cities |website=The Local Government of Quezon City |accessdate=9 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001010801/http://quezoncity.gov.ph/index.php/quezon-city-business-district/350-sister-cities |archivedate=1 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Cebu City]]\n*[[Bayugan]]\n*[[Cotabato City]]\n*[[Zamboanga City]]\n*[[Legazpi, Albay]]\n*[[Bacoor, Cavite]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2016/01/21/Duterte-signs-sister-city-deal-with-Bacoor.html|title=Duterte signs 'sister city' deal with Bacoor|website=cnn}}</ref>\n*[[San Juan, Metro Manila]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/dav/2008/10/05/news/davao.san.juan.cities.ink.sisterhood.pact.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008005240/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/dav/2008/10/05/news/davao.san.juan.cities.ink.sisterhood.pact.html|url-status=dead|title=sunstar.com.ph, Davao, San Juan cities ink sisterhood pact|archive-date=October 8, 2008}}</ref>\n*[[Marikina]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Leonen|first1=Julius|title=Marikina inks sister city agreement with Davao|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1004602/marikina-inks-sister-city-agreement-with-davao|accessdate=1 July 2018|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer#Inquirer.net|INQUIRER.net]]|publisher=INQUIRER.net|date=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!International\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| style=\"width:110%;\"|\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[Jinjiang, Fujian]], China<ref name=\"sunstar1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunstar.com.ph//article/417555/Business/2-friendship-pacts-with-2-cities-inked|title=2 friendship pacts with 2 cities inked|first=Karina C.|last=Ca\u00f1edo|date=February 6, 2018|website=Sunstar}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|China}} [[Nanning]], China\n*{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Manado]], Indonesia\n*{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Pekanbaru]], Indonesia\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Kitakyushu]], Japan\n*{{flagicon|Palau}} [[Koror]], Palau\n*{{flagicon|Uruguay}} [[Montevideo]], Uruguay<ref name=\"SC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.montevideo.gub.uy/institucional/relaciones-internacionales/integracion-regional|publisher=Intendencia Municipal de Montevideo|title=Relaciones internacionales|accessdate=12 December 2011|language=Spanish|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111108082107/http://www.montevideo.gub.uy/institucional/relaciones-internacionales/integracion-regional|archivedate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Panama}} [[Panama City]], Panama<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.munimadrid.es/UnidadWeb/Contenidos/EspecialInformativo/RelacInternac/RRII/HermanamientosyAcuerdos/Files/hermanamiento_UCCI.pdf|title=Declaraci\u00f3n de Hermanamiento m\u00faltiple y solidario de todas las Capitales de Iberoam\u00e9rica (12-10-82)|date=12 October 1982|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510114810/http://www.munimadrid.es/UnidadWeb/Contenidos/EspecialInformativo/RelacInternac/RRII/HermanamientosyAcuerdos/Files/hermanamiento_UCCI.pdf|archivedate=10 May 2013}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Vladivostok]], Russia\n*{{flagicon|Taiwan}} [[Keelung]], Taiwan\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kauai County, Hawaii]], United States<ref name=\"sunstar1\"/>\n*{{flagicon|United States}} [[Tacoma, Washington]], United States\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Friendship cities\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n| style=\"width:110%;\"|\n*{{flagicon|ROK}} [[Uijeongbu]], South Korea<ref name=\"sister-city1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/NewsArticle.aspx?id=28|title=Davao, Korean city to ink sister-city pact}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|ROK}} [[Incheon]], South Korea<ref name=\"sister-city1\" />\n|}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Davao}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Federalism in the Philippines]]\n*[[Tallest buildings in Davao City]]\n*[[Davao International Airport]]\n*[[A.L. Navarro National High School]]\n*[[2017 Davao City mall fire]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.davaocity.gov.ph/ Official Davao City Government Website]\n\n{{Geographic location<!-- This geo box is for DIRECTLY adjacent LGU's as standardized for all other LGU's -->\n| Centre    = Davao City\n| North     = [[Talaingod, Davao del Norte]]\n| Northeast = [[Santo Tomas, Davao del Norte]]<br />[[Braulio E. Dujali, Davao del Norte]]<br />[[Panabo|Panabo, Davao del Norte]]\n| East      = ''[[Davao Gulf]]'' / [[Samal, Davao del Norte]]\n| Southeast = ''[[Davao Gulf]]''\n| South     = [[Digos]] / [[Santa Cruz, Davao del Sur|Santa Cruz]]\n| Southwest = [[Makilala, Cotabato]]<br />[[Bansalan, Davao del Sur|Bansalan]]\n| West      = [[Arakan, Cotabato]]<br />[[Magpet, Cotabato]]\n}}\n\n{{Davao City}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Davao City\n| list  = \n{{Davao del Sur}}\n{{Davao Region}}\n{{Philippine cities}}\n{{Largest cities of the Philippines}}\n{{Largest cities and municipalities in Mindanao}}\n{{Largest Cities in Southeast Asia}}\n{{Most populous cities in Philippines}}\n}}\n\