{"title_page": "Sports in Aruba", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[Aruba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aruba.com/|title=Aruba: Best Island Vacation and Getaway Destination|website=www.aruba.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> is a 19-mile long island in the [[Caribbean]] that hosts many '''sports''', fueling their economy.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAn increase in tourism revenue has led to investment in recreational activities including sports such as [[basketball]] and [[soccer]] to more native pastimes such as [[kite surfing]] and [[spearfishing]]. Aruba has an internationally competing soccer team, and has produced several athletes who have gone on to play in professional leagues.\n[[File:Plaza Daniel Leo, Oranjestad, Aruba - February 2020.jpg|thumb|The Plaza Daniel Leo, located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], is where Aruba's stadiums are located. It is named after a local politician.]]\n\n== Recreational sports ==\nDue to an increase in tourism revenue, Aruba has been able to invest more into sports programs and events. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/world/countries/aruba.htm|title=Sport in Aruba|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Aruba has a competitive recreational basketball team, and citizens are very competitive in baseball and soccer.<ref name=\":1\" />The sport fishing and kite surfing industries have also grown significantly in recent years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Basketball ==\nAruba's recreational [[basketball]] program consists of 16 teams and more than 200 players from the ages of 12 to 18. Basketball clubs have largely contributed to the development of the sport on the island. One of the main objectives of the program is to eventually get one of their athletes an academic scholarship to play in the United States. Aruba is also making efforts to certify one of their referees for international [[FIBA]] events.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/|title=FIBA.basketball|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball ==\n[[Baseball]] is one of the most popular sports on the island and has helped produce many athletes that have gone to the United States to play professionally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bio/Aruba_born.shtml|title=Players by birthplace: Aruba Baseball Stats and Info|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Baseball as a recreational sport originated in the 1930's and many Arubans have grown a passion for it through the years. The first [[Major League Baseball]] player from Aruba was Eugene Humphrey Kingsale who played for a number of professional baseball teams in his 7 year span from 1996-2003. The Aruba Little League originated in 1958 and has continued to grow in popularity since then.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://arubalittleleague.org/|title=Aruba Little League|website=Aruba Little League|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The [[San Nicolaas]] little league team won the 2010 Senior League World Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718151143/http://www.littleleague.org/series/2010divisions/slbb/series.htm|title=Little League Baseball|date=2010-07-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Kite Boarding ==\nThe conditions in Aruba are perfectly suited for [[Kite boarding]] year-round. The island has a favorable wind speeds, averaging around 18.5 miles per hour daily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weatherspark.com/y/26697/Average-Weather-in-Oranjestad-Aruba-Year-Round|title=Average Weather in Oranjestad, Aruba, Year Round - Weather Spark|website=weatherspark.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> As the warm air is less dense than other locations, surfers can use smaller kites than would be needed in other locations. Aruba hosts many global kite boarding tournaments, and the kite boarding industry is one of the largest sources of income for the island.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiteworldmag.com/|title=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|website=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Diving ==\n{{Advert section|date=April 2020}}\nAruba has many diving locations across the island that host tourists and locals throughout the year. The island offers many diving spots including Pedernales, Jane Sea Wreck, Serito Pinnacle, and even several airplane wreckages.<ref name=\":0\" /> The wreck of the [[SS Antilla (1939)]] is one of the largest dive-able wrecks in the Caribbean.\n\n== National Soccer Team ==\nThe men\u2019s [[Aruba national football team]] was founded in 1932 and participated in their first international match on April 6th, 1924. They have had very little success in their international career. The team\u2019s most recent FIFA rank is 203, which is their lowest rank in history, while their highest FIFA rank was 50 in 1924. Their home stadium is the Guillermo Prospero [[Trinidad Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], Aruba. The stadium was originally named after the former Dutch queen [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Wilhelmina]], but was changed to Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium in 1994.\n\nThe women\u2019s Aruban national team\u2019s current head coach is Mildred Wever. Like the men\u2019s team they have not qualified for a [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]]. Their current FIFA ranking is 153, their lowest FIFA ranking is 158, and their highest FIFA ranking is 92. Both teams are a part of an association named Arubaanse Voetbal Bond and both of the teams are a member of the [[CONCACAF]].\n\n== Olympics ==\nIn the past, athletes from Aruba have competed in the Olympics as athletes from the [[Netherlands]], but as of 1986 Aruba now hosts their own athletes. Aruba has competed in 9 Summer [[Olympic Games]], but have not earned any medals. One famous Olympian is [[Miguel Janssen]], who currently holds the country\u2019s record in most long distance running events. He participated for [[Aruba at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Aruba in the 1996 summer games,]] as well as in 6 different world championships for Aruba. Unlike the summer games, Aruba has not participated in any [[Winter Olympic Games|winter games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/events/summer/countries/aruba.htm|title=Aruba at the Olympic Games|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n== Local Sports Facilities ==\nThe Don Elias Mansur Ballpark is a multi-use stadium and is used mainly for baseball games. The Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium is another multi-use stadium and is used by the national soccer teams as well as track and field teams. The Tierra Del Sol Resort, Spa and Country Club is the only 18 hole golf course in Aruba. \n\n== Professional Athletes ==\n\n* [[Calvin Maduro]]\n* [[Gene Kingsale]]\n* [[Radhames Dykhoff]]\n* [[Sidney Ponson]]\n* [[Xander Bogaerts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Sport in Aruba]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[Aruba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aruba.com/|title=Aruba: Best Island Vacation and Getaway Destination|website=www.aruba.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> is a 19 mile long island in the [[Caribbean]] that hosts many '''sports''', fueling their economy.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAn increase in tourism revenue has led to investment in recreational activities including sports such as [[basketball]] and [[soccer]] to more native pastimes such as [[kite surfing]] and [[spearfishing]]. Aruba has an internationally competing soccer team, and has produced several athletes who have gone on to play in professional leagues.\n[[File:Plaza Daniel Leo, Oranjestad, Aruba - February 2020.jpg|thumb|The Plaza Daniel Leo, located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], is where Aruba's stadiums are located. It is named after a local politician.]]\n\n== Recreational sports ==\nDue to an increase in tourism revenue, Aruba has been able to invest more into sports programs and events. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/world/countries/aruba.htm|title=Sport in Aruba|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Aruba has a competitive recreational basketball team, and citizens are very competitive in baseball and soccer.<ref name=\":1\" />The sport fishing and kite surfing industries have also grown significantly in recent years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Basketball ==\nAruba's recreational [[basketball]] program consists of 16 teams and more than 200 players from the ages of 12 to 18. Basketball clubs have largely contributed to the development of the sport on the island. One of the main objectives of the program is to eventually get one of their athletes an academic scholarship to play in the United States. Aruba is also making efforts to certify one of their referees for international [[FIBA]] events.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/|title=FIBA.basketball|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball ==\n[[Baseball]] is one of the most popular sports on the island and has helped produce many athletes that have gone to the United States to play professionally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bio/Aruba_born.shtml|title=Players by birthplace: Aruba Baseball Stats and Info|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Baseball as a recreational sport originated in the 1930's and many Arubans have grown a passion for it through the years. The first [[Major League Baseball]] player from Aruba was Eugene Humphrey Kingsale who played for a number of professional baseball teams in his 7 year span from 1996-2003. The Aruba Little League originated in 1958 and has continued to grow in popularity since then.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://arubalittleleague.org/|title=Aruba Little League|website=Aruba Little League|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The [[San Nicolaas]] little league team won the 2010 Senior League World Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718151143/http://www.littleleague.org/series/2010divisions/slbb/series.htm|title=Little League Baseball|date=2010-07-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Kite Boarding ==\nThe conditions in Aruba are perfectly suited for [[Kite boarding]] year-round. The island has a favorable wind speeds, averaging around 18.5 miles per hour daily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weatherspark.com/y/26697/Average-Weather-in-Oranjestad-Aruba-Year-Round|title=Average Weather in Oranjestad, Aruba, Year Round - Weather Spark|website=weatherspark.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> As the warm air is less dense than other locations, surfers can use smaller kites than would be needed in other locations. Aruba hosts many global kite boarding tournaments, and the kite boarding industry is one of the largest sources of income for the island.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiteworldmag.com/|title=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|website=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Diving ==\n{{Advert section|date=April 2020}}\nAruba has many diving locations across the island that host tourists and locals throughout the year. The island offers many diving spots including Pedernales, Jane Sea Wreck, Serito Pinnacle, and even several airplane wreckages.<ref name=\":0\" /> The wreck of the [[SS Antilla (1939)]] is one of the largest dive-able wrecks in the Caribbean.\n\n== National Soccer Team ==\nThe men\u2019s [[Aruba national football team]] was founded in 1932 and participated in their first international match on April 6th, 1924. They have had very little success in their international career. The team\u2019s most recent FIFA rank is 203, which is their lowest rank in history, while their highest FIFA rank was 50 in 1924. Their home stadium is the Guillermo Prospero [[Trinidad Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], Aruba. The stadium was originally named after the former Dutch queen [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Wilhelmina]], but was changed to Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium in 1994.\n\nThe women\u2019s Aruban national team\u2019s current head coach is Mildred Wever. Like the men\u2019s team they have not qualified for a [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]]. Their current FIFA ranking is 153, their lowest FIFA ranking is 158, and their highest FIFA ranking is 92. Both teams are a part of an association named Arubaanse Voetbal Bond and both of the teams are a member of the [[CONCACAF]].\n\n== Olympics ==\nIn the past, athletes from Aruba have competed in the Olympics as athletes from the [[Netherlands]], but as of 1986 Aruba now hosts their own athletes. Aruba has competed in 9 Summer [[Olympic Games]], but have not earned any medals. One famous Olympian is [[Miguel Janssen]], who currently holds the country\u2019s record in most long distance running events. He participated for [[Aruba at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Aruba in the 1996 summer games,]] as well as in 6 different world championships for Aruba. Unlike the summer games, Aruba has not participated in any [[Winter Olympic Games|winter games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/events/summer/countries/aruba.htm|title=Aruba at the Olympic Games|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n== Local Sports Facilities ==\nThe Don Elias Mansur Ballpark is a multi-use stadium and is used mainly for baseball games. The Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium is another multi-use stadium and is used by the national soccer teams as well as track and field teams. The Tierra Del Sol Resort, Spa and Country Club is the only 18 hole golf course in Aruba. 